00:04:41.996 --> 00:04:44.390
- Well, I gotta say that morals and trade,

00:04:44.390 --> 00:04:47.800
and a moral economy sound
like an oxymoron, doesn't it?

00:04:47.800 --> 00:04:49.150
I mean, there's something a little jarring

00:04:49.150 --> 00:04:52.920
about somebody who gives a
grant to study morals and trade,

00:04:52.920 --> 00:04:55.320
at least in economics
where we try to separate

00:04:55.320 --> 00:04:56.770
these issues as much as possible.

00:04:56.770 --> 00:04:59.120
But, I'll try to convince
you that's a mistake.

00:05:00.150 --> 00:05:04.060
The picture in front of you is a fresco

00:05:04.060 --> 00:05:07.873
in the town hall in Siena
where I often teach.

00:05:08.740 --> 00:05:11.100
And, it's a representation
in the 14th century

00:05:11.100 --> 00:05:12.570
of good government.

00:05:12.570 --> 00:05:15.110
Notice it's a secular image.

00:05:15.110 --> 00:05:17.590
If you look carefully
you can see it's an image

00:05:17.590 --> 00:05:21.020
about commerce and peaceful
intercourse among people.

00:05:21.020 --> 00:05:24.880
The constitution of the town
of Siena at the same time

00:05:24.880 --> 00:05:26.017
made it quite clear, it said,

00:05:26.017 --> 00:05:27.537
"This city must be governed by men

00:05:27.537 --> 00:05:29.540
"who love peace and justice."

00:05:29.540 --> 00:05:33.160
So the a marriage of
morality and good governance

00:05:33.160 --> 00:05:36.420
was the basic idea of that period.

00:05:36.420 --> 00:05:38.210
An idea which came to be displaced

00:05:38.210 --> 00:05:40.610
particularly in economics
in the years later.

00:05:40.610 --> 00:05:41.710
A story which I'll tell.

00:05:41.710 --> 00:05:44.810
And then try to reverse
before we're finished.

00:05:44.810 --> 00:05:46.030
It's a long story.

00:05:46.030 --> 00:05:48.570
So let me give you the basic idea first,

00:05:48.570 --> 00:05:53.090
just a few, there summary points.

00:05:53.090 --> 00:05:54.880
This is what I would like to pursued you

00:05:54.880 --> 00:05:57.383
is worth considering and is perhaps true.

00:05:58.530 --> 00:06:00.650
First, is something which
I think you're aware of,

00:06:00.650 --> 00:06:04.450
it's widely held that in
designing public policies

00:06:04.450 --> 00:06:06.130
and legal systems, and so on,

00:06:06.130 --> 00:06:09.250
we should assume, at least
on grounds of prudence,

00:06:09.250 --> 00:06:12.770
that citizens are entirely
self-interested and amoral.

00:06:12.770 --> 00:06:15.060
That's the so called, Homo
economicus assumption,

00:06:15.060 --> 00:06:17.550
which is the foundation
of the public policy,

00:06:17.550 --> 00:06:19.010
sciences in economics,

00:06:19.010 --> 00:06:20.883
what's called, mechanism
design, and so on.

00:06:20.883 --> 00:06:24.700
And, of course it effects
legal practices as well.

00:06:24.700 --> 00:06:27.080
But, and this is the main point here

00:06:27.080 --> 00:06:29.850
it's anything but prudent to
assume that Homo economicus

00:06:29.850 --> 00:06:33.810
is a good representation of our citizens

00:06:33.810 --> 00:06:35.900
and the people who make
up the body politic

00:06:35.900 --> 00:06:37.120
which we're governing.

00:06:37.120 --> 00:06:39.250
And there are two reasons for this.

00:06:39.250 --> 00:06:41.990
The first is, and I'll try to convince you

00:06:41.990 --> 00:06:44.010
this is really true,

00:06:44.010 --> 00:06:46.820
policies that follow from that paradigm

00:06:46.820 --> 00:06:49.710
are more likely to make
it's assumptions true.

00:06:49.710 --> 00:06:51.830
That is are more likely to convert people

00:06:51.830 --> 00:06:54.090
to acting more like Homo economicus,

00:06:54.090 --> 00:06:57.330
than they would in the
presence of other policies.

00:06:57.330 --> 00:07:00.623
So, the policies are self
defeating and backfire.

00:07:02.270 --> 00:07:04.300
But, the reason why this takes place

00:07:04.300 --> 00:07:07.500
is not per se something
wrong with incentives.

00:07:07.500 --> 00:07:09.540
This is a more subtle point.

00:07:09.540 --> 00:07:12.640
I'm not going to argue here
that incentives are the problem.

00:07:12.640 --> 00:07:14.960
I'm going to argue that
incentives are used

00:07:14.960 --> 00:07:17.610
for purposes that people reject

00:07:17.610 --> 00:07:20.470
because they're either
attempting to implement

00:07:20.470 --> 00:07:24.040
an unfair outcome, or are
attempting to implement

00:07:24.040 --> 00:07:27.870
a type of domination
of the incentive giver

00:07:27.870 --> 00:07:29.750
over the target of the incentives.

00:07:29.750 --> 00:07:32.450
So, we should be thinking,
not about incentives

00:07:32.450 --> 00:07:33.940
as intrinsically a problem,

00:07:33.940 --> 00:07:36.680
but rather the social
relationships that are behind

00:07:36.680 --> 00:07:38.000
the incentives as the problem.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:40.700
And again, I'll try to
give you some reason

00:07:40.700 --> 00:07:42.100
for believing that.

00:07:42.100 --> 00:07:46.640
And finally, in economics
we have a field called,

00:07:46.640 --> 00:07:49.310
mechanism design, in which
we think of very clever ways

00:07:49.310 --> 00:07:51.730
of defining new property
rights, new incentives,

00:07:51.730 --> 00:07:53.510
new constraints and so on.

00:07:53.510 --> 00:07:56.780
Whereby, we can implement
good outcomes no matter what.

00:07:56.780 --> 00:07:58.440
No matter what the people are like.

00:07:58.440 --> 00:08:00.300
I'll return to this theme later.

00:08:00.300 --> 00:08:04.000
But, the conclusion that I
think I will convince you of

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:07.870
is no matter how clever we
are in designing incentives

00:08:07.870 --> 00:08:09.710
and property rights, and so on,

00:08:09.710 --> 00:08:13.100
that alone will never be
sufficient for good governance

00:08:13.100 --> 00:08:16.840
in facing the kinds of problems
that humanity now faces,

00:08:16.840 --> 00:08:19.560
such as, climate change,
mounting inequality,

00:08:19.560 --> 00:08:23.320
economic instability,
political violence, and so on.

00:08:23.320 --> 00:08:25.313
So that's what I'm gonna talk about.

00:08:26.870 --> 00:08:29.473
The ideas, many of them here are not new.

00:08:30.330 --> 00:08:34.550
It begins in the social sciences
with Richard Titmuss's book

00:08:35.400 --> 00:08:36.960
called, The Gift Relationship,

00:08:36.960 --> 00:08:39.227
in which he said, "The
commercialization of blood

00:08:39.227 --> 00:08:43.237
"and donor relationships
represses the expressions

00:08:43.237 --> 00:08:46.247
"of altruism, and erodes
a sense of community."

00:08:47.550 --> 00:08:49.640
The idea was that public spirited motives

00:08:49.640 --> 00:08:53.860
are crowded out by the explicit
application of incentives.

00:08:53.860 --> 00:08:56.730
And therefore, we should
use these incentives less

00:08:56.730 --> 00:08:58.930
because they have that
crowding out feature.

00:09:00.480 --> 00:09:03.070
Now, at the time that he wrote, early 70s,

00:09:03.070 --> 00:09:04.470
there was a lot of research being done.

00:09:04.470 --> 00:09:07.450
A lot of it happen to be in
near by Stanford University,

00:09:07.450 --> 00:09:10.770
by Nisbett, Deci, Green,
others, Lepper in particular

00:09:10.770 --> 00:09:12.053
who I'll come back to.

00:09:13.390 --> 00:09:15.600
That was in psychology it's called

00:09:15.600 --> 00:09:17.763
the over-justification literature.

00:09:17.763 --> 00:09:20.640
An what it shows, for example,
is that you can crowd out

00:09:20.640 --> 00:09:22.150
children's desire to paint

00:09:22.150 --> 00:09:25.183
by paying them for their
paintings, things of that nature.

00:09:27.590 --> 00:09:31.210
So, it received a warm
welcome in psychology

00:09:31.210 --> 00:09:34.470
but a rather chilly one in economics.

00:09:34.470 --> 00:09:39.470
It was surprising, Arrow and
also Solow, reviewed the book

00:09:40.470 --> 00:09:42.390
and I suppose if you're a sociologist

00:09:42.390 --> 00:09:43.520
that's the most you can hope for,

00:09:43.520 --> 00:09:44.740
that an economist would actually

00:09:44.740 --> 00:09:46.760
read your book and review it.

00:09:46.760 --> 00:09:49.060
Two Nobel price winners is not bad.

00:09:49.060 --> 00:09:52.640
But, what they said is,

00:09:52.640 --> 00:09:54.510
they didn't believe
that there was evidence

00:09:54.510 --> 00:09:56.040
for this crowding out phenomenon.

00:09:56.040 --> 00:09:57.573
Here is kind of Arrow,

00:09:58.727 --> 00:10:01.527
"Why should it be that the
creation of a market for blood

00:10:01.527 --> 00:10:04.527
"would decrease the altruism
embodied in giving blood?

00:10:04.527 --> 00:10:07.427
"I do not find any
clear answer in Titmuss.

00:10:07.427 --> 00:10:09.747
"I see no real evidence that the presence

00:10:09.747 --> 00:10:11.037
"of a commercial blood supply

00:10:11.037 --> 00:10:13.027
"decreases the amount of altruism."

00:10:13.890 --> 00:10:14.880
I had the same reaction.

00:10:14.880 --> 00:10:16.860
I read the book with great interest.

00:10:16.860 --> 00:10:19.253
And I didn't think that he made his case.

00:10:21.320 --> 00:10:24.653
Now, of course, since
then a lot has changed.

00:10:26.909 --> 00:10:31.000
The skepticism announced by
these two great economist,

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:34.480
Arrow and Solow, was on
the basis of the fact

00:10:34.480 --> 00:10:36.780
that at the time there was little evidence

00:10:36.780 --> 00:10:38.500
that the kind of moral incentives

00:10:38.500 --> 00:10:41.170
that Titmuss was talking
about were important.

00:10:41.170 --> 00:10:43.030
And there was even less evidence

00:10:43.030 --> 00:10:46.900
that they would be crowded
out by the use of incentives.

00:10:46.900 --> 00:10:49.130
So, Arrow and Solow were on good grounds

00:10:49.130 --> 00:10:51.910
and Titmuss was essentially
making a good argument

00:10:51.910 --> 00:10:54.120
that turned out to be probably correct

00:10:54.120 --> 00:10:55.270
based on later evidence.

00:10:55.270 --> 00:10:56.990
In fact, an unpublished dissertation

00:10:56.990 --> 00:10:58.610
the same year that Titmuss wrote

00:10:58.610 --> 00:10:59.970
made a pretty good case for the fact

00:10:59.970 --> 00:11:00.940
that Titmuss had been right.

00:11:00.940 --> 00:11:04.750
Though Titmuss had been
unaware of this dissertation.

00:11:04.750 --> 00:11:09.750
Now, since then in
economics a lot has changed.

00:11:11.040 --> 00:11:12.150
And here I'm gonna refer

00:11:12.150 --> 00:11:14.128
to things going on within economics.

00:11:14.128 --> 00:11:16.350
Bear with me because
I'll come back to them

00:11:16.350 --> 00:11:17.390
in the course of the talk.

00:11:17.390 --> 00:11:19.980
So if you don't, if you're
not familiar with the themes

00:11:19.980 --> 00:11:22.300
they'll come around again.

00:11:22.300 --> 00:11:25.440
The first is obvious
you all know about this.

00:11:25.440 --> 00:11:29.140
There's now a lot of experimental
evidence in economics

00:11:29.140 --> 00:11:31.670
that these moral incentives
or ethical principles,

00:11:31.670 --> 00:11:33.060
other-regarding preferences,

00:11:33.060 --> 00:11:35.240
generically called, social preferences,

00:11:35.240 --> 00:11:37.640
these are important as
a basis for behavior.

00:11:37.640 --> 00:11:40.690
It doesn't mean they're important
instead of self interest.

00:11:40.690 --> 00:11:42.380
Self interest is also important.

00:11:42.380 --> 00:11:43.850
But, there's no question on the basis

00:11:43.850 --> 00:11:47.460
of the experimental evidence
that our introspection

00:11:47.460 --> 00:11:49.830
and our natural observation around us

00:11:49.830 --> 00:11:52.740
which says to us, yes
other motives matter.

00:11:52.740 --> 00:11:56.433
That is now strongly confirmed
in the experimental evidence.

00:11:58.510 --> 00:12:01.710
Equally important but
a little less obvious.

00:12:01.710 --> 00:12:05.180
Economics has now taken
up the idea as the norm,

00:12:05.180 --> 00:12:07.860
that when I contract
with you for something

00:12:07.860 --> 00:12:10.400
the contract is probably incomplete.

00:12:10.400 --> 00:12:13.110
If I hire you for example, or you hire me,

00:12:13.110 --> 00:12:15.570
the contract says I'm
supposed to show up on time

00:12:15.570 --> 00:12:17.710
and obey the supervisor.

00:12:17.710 --> 00:12:20.190
It doesn't say what
work I'm supposed to do.

00:12:20.190 --> 00:12:21.650
Now, why is that important?

00:12:21.650 --> 00:12:23.590
How does that get norms into play?

00:12:23.590 --> 00:12:25.770
It gets the norms into play directly.

00:12:25.770 --> 00:12:28.673
Because if I hire you I
care about your work ethic.

00:12:29.620 --> 00:12:31.300
If I loan money to you I care about

00:12:31.300 --> 00:12:32.490
whether you're telling me the truth

00:12:32.490 --> 00:12:34.010
about what you're gonna do with the money.

00:12:34.010 --> 00:12:36.470
Because the contract of
a lender to a borrower

00:12:36.470 --> 00:12:37.950
is also incomplete.

00:12:37.950 --> 00:12:41.760
So, because we have, because
most contracts are incomplete

00:12:41.760 --> 00:12:43.580
including very important ones,

00:12:43.580 --> 00:12:45.780
for credit and labor for example,

00:12:45.780 --> 00:12:48.660
it now becomes obvious even to economist

00:12:48.660 --> 00:12:51.130
who have resisted interdisciplinarity,

00:12:51.130 --> 00:12:53.710
it becomes obvious that
the exercise of power

00:12:53.710 --> 00:12:55.690
and the salience of social norms

00:12:55.690 --> 00:12:59.410
is a part of very conventional
economic problems.

00:12:59.410 --> 00:13:01.810
Like, what's the wage,
what's the interest rate?

00:13:02.690 --> 00:13:05.700
Now finally, perhaps even more esoteric

00:13:05.700 --> 00:13:10.450
to those of you who've never
heard of the Lucas critique,

00:13:10.450 --> 00:13:12.710
the Lucas critique is a very important

00:13:12.710 --> 00:13:14.330
intervention in economics.

00:13:14.330 --> 00:13:18.000
And it said, when you
design a economic policy

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:19.433
you have to take account of the effect

00:13:19.433 --> 00:13:21.830
that that policy will have on the beliefs

00:13:21.830 --> 00:13:23.850
that individuals in the society have

00:13:23.850 --> 00:13:25.520
about what's gonna happen next

00:13:25.520 --> 00:13:28.100
and how the government will behave.

00:13:28.100 --> 00:13:30.560
In other words, when you design a policy

00:13:30.560 --> 00:13:34.130
don't take the beliefs
of people as exogenous,

00:13:34.130 --> 00:13:35.830
they'll be affected by the policy.

00:13:35.830 --> 00:13:38.440
Well, all I'm doing here is
I'm taking the Lucas critique

00:13:38.440 --> 00:13:41.020
and instead of applying it to beliefs,

00:13:41.020 --> 00:13:43.280
I'm applying it to norms and values.

00:13:43.280 --> 00:13:46.000
And saying, when you implement a policy

00:13:46.000 --> 00:13:47.670
don't think that the preferences

00:13:47.670 --> 00:13:50.070
which existed before
you had the intervention

00:13:50.070 --> 00:13:51.620
are gonna be around later.

00:13:51.620 --> 00:13:53.253
And I'll come back to that.

00:13:56.180 --> 00:14:00.160
Now, in response to these three things,

00:14:00.160 --> 00:14:03.070
some economists have
rediscovered Aristotle.

00:14:03.070 --> 00:14:04.050
At least that's what they said.

00:14:04.050 --> 00:14:06.683
I suspect that some of them
just had discovered Aristotle.

00:14:06.683 --> 00:14:09.140
(crowd laughing)

00:14:09.140 --> 00:14:11.700
But, if they did, probably the thing

00:14:11.700 --> 00:14:14.000
they would like to read
most is the following.

00:14:14.860 --> 00:14:16.110
This is from, The Ethics.

00:14:16.955 --> 00:14:18.637
"Lawgivers make the citizens good

00:14:18.637 --> 00:14:20.867
"by inculcating habits in them,

00:14:20.867 --> 00:14:23.117
"and this is the aim of every lawgiver.

00:14:23.117 --> 00:14:25.137
"If he does not succeed in doing that,

00:14:25.137 --> 00:14:27.217
"his legislation is a failure.

00:14:27.217 --> 00:14:29.537
"It is in this that a good constitution

00:14:29.537 --> 00:14:31.100
"differs from a bad one."

00:14:31.100 --> 00:14:33.430
Now notice, it's not
this is a characteristic

00:14:33.430 --> 00:14:34.730
of a good constitution.

00:14:34.730 --> 00:14:37.890
This is the characteristic
of a good constitution.

00:14:37.890 --> 00:14:41.000
This is the sine qua non
of a good constitution.

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:44.740
Teaching the public to be good citizens.

00:14:44.740 --> 00:14:48.050
Now, this gives us a dilemma then.

00:14:48.050 --> 00:14:51.030
If Titmuss is right, that
incentives compromise

00:14:51.030 --> 00:14:52.680
the kind of values that we would hope

00:14:52.680 --> 00:14:54.153
to have in a citizenry,

00:14:55.614 --> 00:14:57.614
then what is Aristotle's

00:15:01.240 --> 00:15:04.650
sophisticated legislator supposed to do?

00:15:04.650 --> 00:15:08.510
Because by now Aristotle's
legislator knows

00:15:08.510 --> 00:15:09.900
that incentives are essential.

00:15:09.900 --> 00:15:11.810
You're not gonna run a
society without incentives.

00:15:11.810 --> 00:15:14.200
You're not gonna abolish markets.

00:15:14.200 --> 00:15:16.420
So, we set up a little tension here

00:15:16.420 --> 00:15:21.420
between Titmuss's insight and
Aristotle's view of politics.

00:15:22.640 --> 00:15:24.290
Now, there's one way out of this.

00:15:25.400 --> 00:15:27.563
Maybe we don't have to worry about this.

00:15:29.240 --> 00:15:34.240
Now, economists are really of the view

00:15:34.460 --> 00:15:37.690
that we can do without Aristotle's values.

00:15:37.690 --> 00:15:40.363
That's the way we do our public economics.

00:15:42.630 --> 00:15:45.650
I started to trace where
this idea came from.

00:15:45.650 --> 00:15:49.220
And it really comes not from the meaning

00:15:49.220 --> 00:15:50.560
of an important body of work,

00:15:50.560 --> 00:15:53.130
but rather by a supposition
that has been adopted

00:15:53.130 --> 00:15:56.130
by great thinkers as a thought exercise.

00:15:56.130 --> 00:16:00.193
Think about this, this is Machiavelli.

00:16:01.310 --> 00:16:03.150
I'll come back to the rest of
the quote in just a minute.

00:16:03.150 --> 00:16:05.527
But, the important part in red is,

00:16:05.527 --> 00:16:07.347
"All men are wicked,

00:16:07.347 --> 00:16:09.277
"hunger and poverty make them industrious

00:16:09.277 --> 00:16:10.657
"and laws make them good."

00:16:12.140 --> 00:16:13.390
Does that sound familiar?

00:16:14.410 --> 00:16:18.750
That's the idea that we
can organize a constitution

00:16:18.750 --> 00:16:21.730
on the basis of the incentives,
based on hunger in this case

00:16:21.730 --> 00:16:23.410
to induce people to do things

00:16:23.410 --> 00:16:26.363
which will add up to the social good.

00:16:27.560 --> 00:16:30.900
Now, it's not that of course Machiavelli

00:16:30.900 --> 00:16:33.910
was not saying that
hunger makes people good.

00:16:33.910 --> 00:16:37.390
He says, hunger makes people
act as if they were good.

00:16:37.390 --> 00:16:39.730
And that's good enough.

00:16:39.730 --> 00:16:42.430
Now, there are many
others who had this idea.

00:16:42.430 --> 00:16:45.100
A contemporary of Machiavelli, Marsiglio.

00:16:45.100 --> 00:16:47.210
But also, if you think
about the way Hobbes

00:16:47.210 --> 00:16:50.370
posed the problem of
order and limited freedom

00:16:50.370 --> 00:16:52.300
in what was then modern society.

00:16:52.300 --> 00:16:55.233
Mandeville, Hume, Smith, Bentham.

00:16:56.560 --> 00:16:59.440
Bernard Mandeville, famous in economics

00:16:59.440 --> 00:17:03.010
for a wonderful book that he
wrote, The Fable of the Bees.

00:17:03.010 --> 00:17:05.600
This is what he had to say
about the relationship between

00:17:05.600 --> 00:17:08.127
vice and governance.

00:17:08.127 --> 00:17:10.117
"Thus every part was full of vice.

00:17:10.117 --> 00:17:11.690
"Yet the whole mass of paradise."

00:17:11.690 --> 00:17:15.263
He's describing a hive of
bees were nasty animals.

00:17:16.387 --> 00:17:18.187
"Such were the blessings of that State,

00:17:18.187 --> 00:17:20.557
"their crimes conspired
to make them great.

00:17:20.557 --> 00:17:22.047
"The worst of all the multitude

00:17:22.047 --> 00:17:24.197
"did something for the common good."

00:17:25.060 --> 00:17:27.320
So, this is a really big idea

00:17:27.320 --> 00:17:30.790
that we should distinguish
between motives and consequences.

00:17:30.790 --> 00:17:34.410
And this is Mandeville and
it's of economics after that.

00:17:34.410 --> 00:17:35.863
He wrote it about bees because

00:17:35.863 --> 00:17:38.040
it would have been too scandalous

00:17:38.040 --> 00:17:39.480
at the beginning of the 18th century

00:17:39.480 --> 00:17:40.580
had he written it about humans.

00:17:40.580 --> 00:17:43.750
In fact, he got into a
lot of trouble as it was.

00:17:43.750 --> 00:17:46.570
What happened in the
hive was that the hive

00:17:46.570 --> 00:17:48.070
was this scandalous hive

00:17:48.070 --> 00:17:50.060
and everything work out pretty well.

00:17:50.060 --> 00:17:51.260
But then, they got religion

00:17:51.260 --> 00:17:53.310
and they all acted like good little bees,

00:17:53.310 --> 00:17:54.650
and the hive collapsed and so on.

00:17:54.650 --> 00:17:56.200
That was the story of the bees.

00:17:57.250 --> 00:18:02.250
Now, the subtitle of one of
the additions of his book was,

00:18:03.287 --> 00:18:06.167
"Human frailties may be
turned to the advantage

00:18:06.167 --> 00:18:08.267
"of civil society and made to supply

00:18:08.267 --> 00:18:10.077
"the place of moral virtue."

00:18:11.350 --> 00:18:13.790
Now that is a very very interesting idea.

00:18:13.790 --> 00:18:18.790
That is, the ordinary motives
could substitute for virtues.

00:18:19.670 --> 00:18:22.210
He didn't explain how that could be done.

00:18:22.210 --> 00:18:24.670
But, it would very soon be provided

00:18:24.670 --> 00:18:26.440
by the classical economists.

00:18:26.440 --> 00:18:27.600
The invisible hand is

00:18:27.600 --> 00:18:30.030
of course just a statement of that view.

00:18:30.030 --> 00:18:33.240
That ordinary motives
when organized properly

00:18:33.240 --> 00:18:34.910
by the proper social institutions

00:18:34.910 --> 00:18:37.730
can induce people to
act in the public good.

00:18:37.730 --> 00:18:41.210
So, here we have one of
the most famous quotes

00:18:41.210 --> 00:18:44.057
even rivaling one where
mentions the invisible hand,

00:18:44.057 --> 00:18:46.087
"It's not from the
benevolence of the butcher

00:18:46.087 --> 00:18:48.537
"the brewer, or the baker
that we expect our dinner,

00:18:48.537 --> 00:18:51.607
"but from their regard
to their self interest."

00:18:53.253 --> 00:18:57.420
Now, this view was taken
up by people at the time.

00:18:59.070 --> 00:19:00.830
Hume, of course, preceded Adam Smith

00:19:00.830 --> 00:19:02.323
by about half a generation.

00:19:03.270 --> 00:19:05.830
And, what Hume said about policy making

00:19:05.830 --> 00:19:08.440
and constitution making, really epitomizes

00:19:08.440 --> 00:19:11.387
the way modern economists have thought.

00:19:11.387 --> 00:19:14.567
"Political writers have
established it as a maxim

00:19:14.567 --> 00:19:17.107
"that in contriving any
system of government

00:19:17.107 --> 00:19:20.177
"every man ought to be
supposed to be a knave

00:19:20.177 --> 00:19:22.277
"and to have no other
end in all of his actions

00:19:22.277 --> 00:19:23.847
"than his private interest.

00:19:23.847 --> 00:19:25.777
"By this interest we must govern him

00:19:25.777 --> 00:19:28.367
"and by means of it make
him, notwithstanding

00:19:28.367 --> 00:19:30.517
"his insatiable avarice and ambition,

00:19:30.517 --> 00:19:32.467
"cooperate to public good."

00:19:33.390 --> 00:19:35.100
Now by the way, doesn't it sound like

00:19:35.100 --> 00:19:36.970
he must have been reading Machiavelli?

00:19:36.970 --> 00:19:39.120
Even the structure of
the sentences, right?

00:19:40.052 --> 00:19:41.820
Anybody who wants to form a republic

00:19:41.820 --> 00:19:44.080
should supposed that,
that's the translation

00:19:44.080 --> 00:19:45.433
of Machiavelli's Italian.

00:19:46.380 --> 00:19:47.880
Hume is saying the same thing.

00:19:49.270 --> 00:19:52.280
And, we get Bentham who
wrote the first book

00:19:52.280 --> 00:19:55.060
in what we would now
call public economics.

00:19:55.060 --> 00:19:56.963
How to design public policies.

00:19:58.190 --> 00:20:01.530
He announced what he called
his duty on interest principle.

00:20:01.530 --> 00:20:04.370
He was talking about
compensation of public officials.

00:20:04.370 --> 00:20:08.677
And he said, "We should
make it every man's interest

00:20:08.677 --> 00:20:13.677
"to observe that conduct which
it is his duty to observe."

00:20:13.760 --> 00:20:16.520
Now, in economics we just
call that aligning incentives.

00:20:16.520 --> 00:20:18.680
Or, an incentive compatible policy.

00:20:18.680 --> 00:20:21.290
That is, it's a policy that induces people

00:20:21.290 --> 00:20:22.820
as a result of their self interest

00:20:22.820 --> 00:20:26.090
to do the thing that
the society as a whole

00:20:26.090 --> 00:20:29.340
would deem profitable
or good for the society.

00:20:29.340 --> 00:20:33.400
And once again, these two statements here

00:20:33.400 --> 00:20:38.400
are about not making people
care about their morality

00:20:38.460 --> 00:20:39.730
or the benefits they give to others,

00:20:39.730 --> 00:20:42.090
but rather given them
private incentives to do so

00:20:42.090 --> 00:20:44.573
by the clever design of public policy.

00:20:45.720 --> 00:20:50.410
And so, what happened during this period

00:20:50.410 --> 00:20:52.883
from Machiavelli through to Bentham,

00:20:54.050 --> 00:20:56.620
was that good laws replaced good citizens

00:20:56.620 --> 00:20:58.603
as the sine qua non of good government.

00:20:59.580 --> 00:21:02.270
We could displace Aristotle concern

00:21:02.270 --> 00:21:04.640
by the design of good principles.

00:21:04.640 --> 00:21:07.020
And that was by the way a very key idea

00:21:07.020 --> 00:21:08.450
in Machiavelli's Discourses.

00:21:08.450 --> 00:21:10.170
Not, The Prince, but in The Discourses.

00:21:10.170 --> 00:21:11.390
That's what he's really saying.

00:21:11.390 --> 00:21:13.010
The thing that we have that we can do

00:21:13.010 --> 00:21:15.430
is we can design roles
which will induce people

00:21:15.430 --> 00:21:17.650
as he put it, of ordinary humors,

00:21:17.650 --> 00:21:19.740
we can induce people of ordinary humors

00:21:19.740 --> 00:21:21.247
to conduct themselves in way

00:21:21.247 --> 00:21:23.047
that contributes to the public good.

00:21:24.190 --> 00:21:26.480
And this is really a big
idea right up to the present.

00:21:26.480 --> 00:21:27.970
I think it's familiar to you.

00:21:27.970 --> 00:21:32.640
But, this is a wonderful
editorial from 1988

00:21:32.640 --> 00:21:33.800
from The New York Times.

00:21:33.800 --> 00:21:35.743
A previous financial crisis.

00:21:37.630 --> 00:21:40.850
Program, trading, index
arbitrage and so on.

00:21:40.850 --> 00:21:43.787
Could go on about this
but the key line is this,

00:21:43.787 --> 00:21:46.177
"Perhaps the most
important idea here is that

00:21:46.177 --> 00:21:49.307
"to distinguish between
motive and consequence.

00:21:49.307 --> 00:21:51.357
"Derivative securities attract the greedy

00:21:51.357 --> 00:21:53.487
"the way raw meat attracts piranhas.

00:21:53.487 --> 00:21:54.447
"But so what?

00:21:54.447 --> 00:21:56.137
"Private greed can lead to public good.

00:21:56.137 --> 00:21:58.257
"The sensible goal for
securities regulation

00:21:58.257 --> 00:22:02.100
"is to channel selfish
behavior, not to thwart it."

00:22:02.100 --> 00:22:04.690
And I'm imagining that
that was written by some,

00:22:04.690 --> 00:22:07.720
that line was put in there
by some Yale graduate

00:22:07.720 --> 00:22:10.720
from economics who was
assisting the editorial board,

00:22:10.720 --> 00:22:13.420
had read Mandeville and so on.

00:22:13.420 --> 00:22:15.100
And thought that was a
clever thing to put in.

00:22:15.100 --> 00:22:16.600
It's just straight Mandeville.

00:22:17.470 --> 00:22:22.060
Now, so now think about it.

00:22:22.060 --> 00:22:25.260
It may be repugnant to
you to think that way.

00:22:25.260 --> 00:22:27.163
But, should we worry really?

00:22:28.530 --> 00:22:30.293
Why not just harness greed?

00:22:32.274 --> 00:22:35.691
Well, economist say that a market economy

00:22:37.710 --> 00:22:40.230
or a capitalistic economy has the benefit

00:22:40.230 --> 00:22:43.643
of not relying on
morality to function well.

00:22:44.620 --> 00:22:49.487
Of course, a very famous
expositor of this view is Hayek.

00:22:49.487 --> 00:22:51.697
"The liberal market economy
is a system under which

00:22:51.697 --> 00:22:53.487
"bad men can do least harm.

00:22:53.487 --> 00:22:56.237
"It does not require out
finding good men for running it,

00:22:56.237 --> 00:23:00.020
"or that on all men becoming
better than they are now."

00:23:00.020 --> 00:23:01.440
That's just Machiavelli.

00:23:01.440 --> 00:23:04.840
Ordinary humors, that's all we need.

00:23:04.840 --> 00:23:06.620
A little more explicitly Charles Schultze

00:23:06.620 --> 00:23:08.827
of the Brookings Institution.

00:23:08.827 --> 00:23:11.727
"Market-like arrangements
reduce the need for compassion,

00:23:11.727 --> 00:23:14.950
"patriotism, brotherly love
and cultural solidarity."

00:23:14.950 --> 00:23:19.393
And finally, I think the
most astute one is Buchanan.

00:23:20.540 --> 00:23:22.530
Nobel laureate in economics.

00:23:22.530 --> 00:23:27.097
He's shopping near his home in Virginia.

00:23:27.097 --> 00:23:29.047
"I do not know the fruit
salesman personally,

00:23:29.047 --> 00:23:31.257
"I have no particular
interest in his wellbeing.

00:23:31.257 --> 00:23:33.267
"he reciprocates this attitude.

00:23:33.267 --> 00:23:35.637
"I do not know, and have no need to know,

00:23:35.637 --> 00:23:37.580
"whether he is in the direst of poverty,

00:23:37.580 --> 00:23:39.897
extremely wealthy, or
somewhere in between.

00:23:39.897 --> 00:23:42.707
"Yet, the two of us are
able to transact exchanges

00:23:42.707 --> 00:23:45.507
"efficiently because both parties agree

00:23:45.507 --> 00:23:48.692
"on the property rights relevant to them."

00:23:48.692 --> 00:23:51.340
Now that is a very bright statement.

00:23:51.340 --> 00:23:53.330
I mean, I don't endorse his indifference

00:23:53.330 --> 00:23:54.900
towards the fruit salesman.

00:23:54.900 --> 00:23:58.360
But, he understands what
it is about the economics.

00:23:58.360 --> 00:24:01.190
Which, I'm happy to say,
we can now call former

00:24:01.190 --> 00:24:03.010
economic conventional economics.

00:24:03.010 --> 00:24:05.260
Which is no longer taught in grad school

00:24:05.260 --> 00:24:06.517
thank you very much.

00:24:06.517 --> 00:24:10.070
"Because we agree on the property
rights relevant to them."

00:24:10.070 --> 00:24:11.640
That's just another statement for saying

00:24:11.640 --> 00:24:13.280
the contract is complete.

00:24:13.280 --> 00:24:16.380
Everything that we care about
has been contracted for.

00:24:16.380 --> 00:24:18.980
So I don't care about his morality.

00:24:18.980 --> 00:24:20.590
If he gives me a bag of bananas,

00:24:20.590 --> 00:24:21.770
and it's not a bag of bananas,

00:24:21.770 --> 00:24:23.690
I get my money back.

00:24:23.690 --> 00:24:24.970
So that's what he's saying,

00:24:24.970 --> 00:24:28.450
complete contract is what
makes his indifference

00:24:28.450 --> 00:24:29.823
an appropriate stance.

00:24:31.420 --> 00:24:35.123
Well, but economist have had,

00:24:36.010 --> 00:24:38.720
you may wonder why I said it was ex.

00:24:38.720 --> 00:24:39.553
Did you wonder?

00:24:39.553 --> 00:24:40.390
It is ex.

00:24:40.390 --> 00:24:41.400
I'm coming to that.

00:24:41.400 --> 00:24:42.970
Why it is that we once thought that

00:24:42.970 --> 00:24:44.270
but we no longer think it?

00:24:47.380 --> 00:24:48.470
Why did economist think that

00:24:48.470 --> 00:24:50.660
we should be concerned with preferences?

00:24:50.660 --> 00:24:52.710
We could put them aside.

00:24:52.710 --> 00:24:55.510
Well, we once had a theory that showed

00:24:55.510 --> 00:24:57.870
that desirable social outcomes

00:24:57.870 --> 00:25:00.920
are possible with
unrestricted preferences.

00:25:00.920 --> 00:25:02.820
So, let me run through this argument.

00:25:02.820 --> 00:25:07.820
Unrestricted preferences mean
essentially, bring them on.

00:25:07.880 --> 00:25:11.320
We don't care what the preferences
are, we can handle them.

00:25:11.320 --> 00:25:13.960
So, here I'll lay out in a single slide

00:25:13.960 --> 00:25:16.300
what the argument is and then
I'll tell you why it's wrong

00:25:16.300 --> 00:25:18.840
and why economist have now rejected it.

00:25:18.840 --> 00:25:21.800
First, the market is
obviously decentralized

00:25:21.800 --> 00:25:23.490
it's privacy preserving.

00:25:23.490 --> 00:25:27.530
It's, when guided possibly by a good

00:25:27.530 --> 00:25:32.530
but not omniscient planner
or social designer,

00:25:32.650 --> 00:25:35.710
policy maker, it's capable
of implementing outcomes

00:25:36.720 --> 00:25:38.320
by means of procedures.

00:25:38.320 --> 00:25:40.330
And the italicized parts
are the three things

00:25:40.330 --> 00:25:43.770
that matter as far as a
liberal commitment like that

00:25:43.770 --> 00:25:45.223
of, for example, Hayek.

00:25:47.100 --> 00:25:49.200
That is, it avoids coercion.

00:25:49.200 --> 00:25:52.640
It avoids paternalism
and it's free of waste.

00:25:52.640 --> 00:25:53.830
Those three things.

00:25:53.830 --> 00:25:54.980
I'll come back to them.

00:25:56.720 --> 00:25:57.800
It avoids waste.

00:25:57.800 --> 00:25:59.970
What we mean in economics by that is just

00:25:59.970 --> 00:26:01.970
the outcome is Pareto efficient.

00:26:01.970 --> 00:26:03.973
It's not possible in the outcome

00:26:03.973 --> 00:26:07.000
for all parties to be made
better off by some change

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:09.500
without anyone being made worse off.

00:26:09.500 --> 00:26:11.990
So that's the rather
minimalist view of efficiency

00:26:11.990 --> 00:26:14.083
which is part of this liberal commitment.

00:26:15.040 --> 00:26:17.040
It avoids paternalism.

00:26:17.040 --> 00:26:19.180
It doesn't say that people have to be

00:26:19.180 --> 00:26:20.870
of one type of preference or the other.

00:26:20.870 --> 00:26:23.160
It completely rejects Aristotle's view

00:26:23.160 --> 00:26:25.230
that he constitution
should take a position

00:26:25.230 --> 00:26:28.340
on what the citizens should be like.

00:26:28.340 --> 00:26:30.910
So by unrestricted preferences it means,

00:26:30.910 --> 00:26:33.160
that you can any preferences you want.

00:26:33.160 --> 00:26:36.190
This is now, it's called
preference neutrality

00:26:36.190 --> 00:26:37.620
among liberal philosophers.

00:26:37.620 --> 00:26:38.760
By the way, it's a very new term.

00:26:38.760 --> 00:26:40.520
It's not an ancient term.

00:26:40.520 --> 00:26:43.070
But it just means, if you're a liberal

00:26:43.070 --> 00:26:45.660
you don't make a position
about the nature of the good,

00:26:45.660 --> 00:26:48.890
or what people consider to
be the good life and so on.

00:26:48.890 --> 00:26:52.220
And finally, whatever the outcome is

00:26:52.220 --> 00:26:53.760
it should avoid coercion.

00:26:53.760 --> 00:26:56.763
If you participate in an
exchange it has to be voluntary.

00:26:58.130 --> 00:26:59.290
Now think about it.

00:26:59.290 --> 00:27:02.330
That's not all you could
ask of a philosophy

00:27:02.330 --> 00:27:03.890
as the basis for economics.

00:27:03.890 --> 00:27:05.760
But you must agree, that's pretty basic.

00:27:05.760 --> 00:27:07.560
Those are things that liberal people,

00:27:07.560 --> 00:27:11.193
I count myself among them,
liberal people are committed to.

00:27:13.680 --> 00:27:16.473
Now, some people think
that it's been done.

00:27:17.570 --> 00:27:21.500
A great professor from
this great university

00:27:21.500 --> 00:27:23.713
certainly claimed that it had been done.

00:27:26.487 --> 00:27:27.980
"The superiority of liberalism

00:27:27.980 --> 00:27:31.387
has been mathematically
demonstrated," by Gerard Debreu.

00:27:32.810 --> 00:27:33.643
This is in Figaro.

00:27:33.643 --> 00:27:35.820
Actually, Figaro misquoted
him in the headline.

00:27:35.820 --> 00:27:39.080
What he said actually,
was virtually identical,

00:27:39.080 --> 00:27:40.167
what he said is,

00:27:40.167 --> 00:27:43.457
"The superiority of the liberal
economy is incontestable

00:27:43.457 --> 00:27:46.270
"and can be demonstrated mathematically."

00:27:46.270 --> 00:27:48.420
He was talking about the famous theorem,

00:27:48.420 --> 00:27:49.880
so called, invisible hand theorem,

00:27:49.880 --> 00:27:53.240
the he and Kenneth Arrow
proved 30 years earlier,

00:27:53.240 --> 00:27:55.320
which showed the conditions under which

00:27:55.320 --> 00:27:57.140
a competitive economy would support

00:27:57.140 --> 00:27:58.573
a Pareto efficient outcome.

00:28:00.370 --> 00:28:04.470
So, let's think of this liberal trinity.

00:28:04.470 --> 00:28:05.890
Has it been demonstrated?

00:28:05.890 --> 00:28:09.181
Those are the three desiderata
that I mentioned before.

00:28:09.181 --> 00:28:10.210
Pareto efficiency,

00:28:10.210 --> 00:28:12.560
preference neutrality,
voluntary participation.

00:28:14.813 --> 00:28:19.813
Now, so this is what economist
thought as of the late 80s

00:28:21.130 --> 00:28:23.260
that we, I mean, or the early 80s,

00:28:23.260 --> 00:28:24.610
that we had actually shown.

00:28:25.640 --> 00:28:29.220
And, let me say why we thought that.

00:28:29.220 --> 00:28:32.380
That is, we had some theories

00:28:32.380 --> 00:28:34.010
under the heading of mechanism design

00:28:34.010 --> 00:28:34.923
which appeared to show that implement

00:28:34.923 --> 00:28:38.170
Pareto efficient outcomes
with unrestricted preferences

00:28:38.170 --> 00:28:40.130
and with voluntary participation.

00:28:40.130 --> 00:28:44.555
But, that hope turned out to be false.

00:28:44.555 --> 00:28:47.210
For decades of mechanism design,

00:28:47.210 --> 00:28:51.110
and a good number of Nobel
prices for these results showed,

00:28:51.110 --> 00:28:52.330
and I'm summarizing here,

00:28:52.330 --> 00:28:54.070
what the Swedish Nobel Committee said

00:28:54.070 --> 00:28:56.781
in awarding the prizes the first time,

00:28:56.781 --> 00:28:59.077
the really big mechanism
designer got prizes,

00:28:59.077 --> 00:29:01.397
"The implementation of
Pareto-efficient outcomes

00:29:01.397 --> 00:29:04.157
"in the absence of complete
contracts is generally

00:29:04.157 --> 00:29:07.017
"impossible for unrestricted preferences

00:29:07.017 --> 00:29:08.927
"if participation is voluntary

00:29:08.927 --> 00:29:10.837
"and there's a limit on
the extent of penalties

00:29:10.837 --> 00:29:13.537
"that may be imposed,
excluding physical punishment

00:29:13.537 --> 00:29:15.690
"imprisonment for debt," and so on.

00:29:15.690 --> 00:29:17.683
That's the result of this body of work.

00:29:18.720 --> 00:29:20.460
Now, there are many parts of it.

00:29:20.460 --> 00:29:22.460
Getting people to truthfully tell

00:29:22.460 --> 00:29:25.020
what their preferences
are, or their capacity

00:29:25.020 --> 00:29:27.840
turns out to be not incentive compatible.

00:29:27.840 --> 00:29:30.450
That is, you can't design
a way that does that

00:29:30.450 --> 00:29:31.860
if there are more than two options.

00:29:31.860 --> 00:29:33.980
That was shown in 75.

00:29:33.980 --> 00:29:36.670
Private voluntary exchange,
even when you have

00:29:36.670 --> 00:29:40.783
complete contracts does not
implement efficient outcomes.

00:29:41.630 --> 00:29:44.300
That was shown by Myerson
and Satterthwaite,

00:29:44.300 --> 00:29:46.850
and Chatterjee, and Samuelson
also in the late 80s.

00:29:47.690 --> 00:29:50.260
Now as result, the
mechanism design literature

00:29:50.260 --> 00:29:51.660
has for the most part abandoned

00:29:51.660 --> 00:29:53.510
the Pareto criterion entirely.

00:29:53.510 --> 00:29:55.690
And what it does, it talks
about something called

00:29:55.690 --> 00:29:56.870
incentive efficiency.

00:29:56.870 --> 00:30:00.970
Which means, the best you
can do given the preferences.

00:30:00.970 --> 00:30:03.870
Which obviously means that
then preferences are important.

00:30:04.800 --> 00:30:06.320
They've abandoned the idea,

00:30:06.320 --> 00:30:08.363
the strong idea of Pareto efficiency.

00:30:09.510 --> 00:30:11.970
And these are the guys
Hurwicz, Myerson and Maskin

00:30:11.970 --> 00:30:16.830
who one the price for
their contribution to this.

00:30:16.830 --> 00:30:20.520
Now, a number of people
have worked on this problem.

00:30:20.520 --> 00:30:23.983
And, I wanna say that this
is a trilemma, not a trinity.

00:30:25.053 --> 00:30:29.500
And, the idea is you can
have any two vertices

00:30:29.500 --> 00:30:30.400
but not all three.

00:30:31.300 --> 00:30:33.650
And, I'll show some results on the edges

00:30:33.650 --> 00:30:35.290
about why that's true.

00:30:35.290 --> 00:30:37.593
And what you lose if you do,

00:30:39.650 --> 00:30:44.360
for example, you can
have Pareto efficiency

00:30:44.360 --> 00:30:46.023
and voluntary participation,

00:30:49.790 --> 00:30:51.380
but you can't have preference neutrality.

00:30:51.380 --> 00:30:53.530
So, if you have that one and that one

00:30:53.530 --> 00:30:55.130
what Hwang, that's Hwang there,

00:30:55.130 --> 00:30:58.700
what Hwang and I showed
is you can have these two

00:30:58.700 --> 00:31:01.620
but only by violating
preference neutrality.

00:31:01.620 --> 00:31:04.430
If at least, by the way it's not true

00:31:04.430 --> 00:31:08.020
that both of the agents have
to be honest or altruistic,

00:31:08.020 --> 00:31:10.990
just one, but they have
to be sufficiently so.

00:31:10.990 --> 00:31:13.270
So you have to violate the idea that,

00:31:13.270 --> 00:31:15.653
bring them on, when it
comes to preferences.

00:31:17.120 --> 00:31:19.030
You can have voluntary participation

00:31:19.030 --> 00:31:20.700
and preference neutrality,

00:31:20.700 --> 00:31:23.220
but this is what Chatterjee
and Samuelson showed,

00:31:23.220 --> 00:31:25.500
then there'll be unrealized
gains from trade.

00:31:25.500 --> 00:31:30.400
And you can have Pareto efficiency
and preference neutrality

00:31:30.400 --> 00:31:32.740
but only by a very clever mechanism

00:31:32.740 --> 00:31:35.260
which requires people to
commit to making a trade

00:31:35.260 --> 00:31:37.610
before they find out what the deal is.

00:31:37.610 --> 00:31:38.590
In which some of them,

00:31:38.590 --> 00:31:40.060
once they find out what the deal is

00:31:40.060 --> 00:31:41.470
they won't wanna be part of it.

00:31:41.470 --> 00:31:44.173
So, that violates voluntary participation.

00:31:50.242 --> 00:31:53.140
So, I conclude that that attempt failed

00:31:53.140 --> 00:31:55.990
and it failed, you know, a long time ago.

00:31:55.990 --> 00:31:59.120
Interestingly the paper
from Figaro in which

00:31:59.120 --> 00:32:00.853
Debreu was quoted was exactly the time

00:32:00.853 --> 00:32:02.630
that these papers were coming out.

00:32:02.630 --> 00:32:06.150
And he, Debreu, was extremely
on top of that literature

00:32:06.150 --> 00:32:07.850
to his wonderful credit.

00:32:07.850 --> 00:32:10.020
Why he said that to Figaro I can't imagine

00:32:10.020 --> 00:32:13.090
because the house of cards was collapsing

00:32:13.090 --> 00:32:14.700
right in those years.

00:32:14.700 --> 00:32:17.460
And the date in Figaro was 84,

00:32:17.460 --> 00:32:20.220
and these papers were
all in the early 80s.

00:32:20.220 --> 00:32:25.220
Now, so virtue, to use
the old style expression,

00:32:27.700 --> 00:32:29.470
it is still essential.

00:32:29.470 --> 00:32:32.000
And this is especially the case

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:35.150
where relevant information
is not verifiable.

00:32:35.150 --> 00:32:37.810
The non-verifiability of information

00:32:37.810 --> 00:32:40.440
is what gives rise to
incomplete contracts.

00:32:40.440 --> 00:32:42.030
If there's some kind of information

00:32:42.030 --> 00:32:45.240
that either is lacking, so
called asymmetric information,

00:32:45.240 --> 00:32:47.940
or even if present can't
be used in a court of law

00:32:47.940 --> 00:32:49.510
to enforce a contract,

00:32:49.510 --> 00:32:51.820
then you'll have an incomplete contract

00:32:51.820 --> 00:32:54.410
and then all of these problems will arise

00:32:54.410 --> 00:32:57.173
and norms and other things
will become necessary.

00:32:58.630 --> 00:33:02.760
It's also the case that imagine a state

00:33:02.760 --> 00:33:05.860
that had the capability
of implementing a system

00:33:05.860 --> 00:33:08.380
whereby contracts would be complete.

00:33:08.380 --> 00:33:10.690
That would be an extremely invasive state

00:33:10.690 --> 00:33:12.620
capable of collecting information from you

00:33:12.620 --> 00:33:14.480
which is, now it cannot be collected.

00:33:14.480 --> 00:33:16.670
In other words, trying to
make all the information

00:33:16.670 --> 00:33:19.300
about your life verifiable in a court

00:33:19.300 --> 00:33:21.260
is exactly what most liberal people

00:33:21.260 --> 00:33:23.890
on privacy grounds would resist.

00:33:23.890 --> 00:33:26.490
So, making the liberal economy

00:33:26.490 --> 00:33:28.130
that is the neoclassical model

00:33:28.130 --> 00:33:30.150
which was supposed to
be the economic basis

00:33:30.150 --> 00:33:31.680
of the liberal philosophy,

00:33:31.680 --> 00:33:35.000
making it work is a dystopic vision

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:37.340
because it would require
contracts to be complete

00:33:37.340 --> 00:33:38.330
which would require a state

00:33:38.330 --> 00:33:40.030
that no liberal would ever accept.

00:33:42.080 --> 00:33:45.520
Now, other regarding preferences,

00:33:45.520 --> 00:33:48.480
ethical commitments become important.

00:33:48.480 --> 00:33:50.020
And here we have Arrow again

00:33:50.020 --> 00:33:53.743
once again getting it
right, 1971 he wrote this.

00:33:54.587 --> 00:33:56.317
"The process of exchanges requires

00:33:56.317 --> 00:33:58.127
"or at least is greatly facilitated

00:33:58.127 --> 00:34:01.247
"by the the presence of several virtues,

00:34:01.247 --> 00:34:03.437
"not only truth, but also trust, loyalty

00:34:03.437 --> 00:34:05.950
"and justice in future dealings."

00:34:05.950 --> 00:34:07.397
Again, still Arrow,

00:34:07.397 --> 00:34:09.417
"In the absence of trust opportunities

00:34:09.417 --> 00:34:11.067
"for mutually beneficial cooperation

00:34:11.067 --> 00:34:12.677
"would have to be forgone.

00:34:12.677 --> 00:34:15.767
"Norms of social behavior
including ethical and moral codes

00:34:15.767 --> 00:34:18.197
"may be reactions of society to compensate

00:34:18.197 --> 00:34:19.637
"for market failures."

00:34:21.390 --> 00:34:23.201
Once again, he's got it right except

00:34:23.201 --> 00:34:25.180
it's suggesting that
we had market failures

00:34:25.180 --> 00:34:28.070
before we had morals is
a little bit ahistorical

00:34:28.070 --> 00:34:30.190
because clearly human being had morals

00:34:30.190 --> 00:34:31.350
long before they had markets

00:34:31.350 --> 00:34:33.400
and therefore they couldn't
of had market failures.

00:34:33.400 --> 00:34:36.780
But I'll set aside for the
great and sadly departed

00:34:36.780 --> 00:34:38.323
economist Kenneth Arrow.

00:34:40.640 --> 00:34:44.163
Now, let's think about
were economics went wrong.

00:34:47.250 --> 00:34:52.250
The classical writers assumed something

00:34:53.670 --> 00:34:55.720
that nobody's really put their finger on.

00:34:56.820 --> 00:34:59.220
They did not assume that
people were selfish,

00:34:59.220 --> 00:35:00.113
far from it.

00:35:01.440 --> 00:35:03.780
They didn't assume that
preferences were somehow

00:35:03.780 --> 00:35:06.060
outside of economics or exogenous.

00:35:06.060 --> 00:35:10.050
I mean think about,
Hume's moral convention.

00:35:10.050 --> 00:35:12.660
Hume who said we should act
as if people were knaves

00:35:12.660 --> 00:35:16.510
the next sentence said it
may seem odd to you reader

00:35:16.510 --> 00:35:19.150
that something which is
a true axiom for politics

00:35:19.150 --> 00:35:20.673
should be false in fact.

00:35:21.520 --> 00:35:22.610
That's what he said.

00:35:22.610 --> 00:35:24.940
We're gonna assume this
and we know it's not true.

00:35:24.940 --> 00:35:28.350
Or, think about Adam Smith,
Theory of Moral Sentiments,

00:35:28.350 --> 00:35:29.640
very aware of that.

00:35:29.640 --> 00:35:31.317
Let's go back to Machiavelli.

00:35:31.317 --> 00:35:36.025
"It's necessary to anyone
who would organize a republic

00:35:36.025 --> 00:35:39.387
"and it's laws in the republic

00:35:39.387 --> 00:35:43.630
"to suppose that people are wicked."

00:35:43.630 --> 00:35:45.390
He didn't say people are wicked.

00:35:45.390 --> 00:35:47.420
He said, you should adapt this assumption

00:35:47.420 --> 00:35:50.530
if you're gonna design a constitution.

00:35:50.530 --> 00:35:52.860
We want to, or as Hume put it,

00:35:52.860 --> 00:35:54.750
we want a knave proof constitution.

00:35:54.750 --> 00:35:56.853
We want a wicked proof constitution.

00:35:57.790 --> 00:35:59.680
And in fact, Machiavelli went on and on

00:35:59.680 --> 00:36:01.250
about how societies were well governed

00:36:01.250 --> 00:36:03.970
where they have high levels of morals.

00:36:03.970 --> 00:36:05.850
People misunderstand what
Machiavelli was all about.

00:36:05.850 --> 00:36:07.650
Read The Discourses, not The Prince.

00:36:09.130 --> 00:36:14.130
Now, so they were very aware
of the importance of norms.

00:36:14.200 --> 00:36:17.140
But, they did make the
following assumption,

00:36:17.140 --> 00:36:19.760
they assumed that what Smith
called moral sentiments

00:36:19.760 --> 00:36:22.300
and material interest could
be pursued independently.

00:36:22.300 --> 00:36:24.350
That is, they assumed that policies

00:36:24.350 --> 00:36:25.860
which were designed to shape behavior

00:36:25.860 --> 00:36:29.570
by appealing to the material interest

00:36:29.570 --> 00:36:31.720
in monetary incentive for example,

00:36:31.720 --> 00:36:33.890
wouldn't interfere with
the moral sentiments.

00:36:33.890 --> 00:36:36.870
Which might also assist
in governing a society.

00:36:36.870 --> 00:36:39.640
And similarly, that appeal
to the moral sentiments

00:36:39.640 --> 00:36:40.890
would not interfere with

00:36:40.890 --> 00:36:44.120
the exercise of the material interests.

00:36:44.120 --> 00:36:47.870
So, the key idea here is that
incentives affect actions

00:36:47.870 --> 00:36:49.820
only by altering the cost and benefits

00:36:49.820 --> 00:36:51.450
of the targeted activities.

00:36:51.450 --> 00:36:53.500
So, there's no effect on the preferences.

00:36:54.580 --> 00:36:59.580
Now, these proposition
as you will recognize

00:36:59.870 --> 00:37:03.360
now come into play in policies to get kids

00:37:03.360 --> 00:37:05.250
to stay in school, to not get pregnant,

00:37:05.250 --> 00:37:07.170
sentencing guidelines,

00:37:07.170 --> 00:37:10.130
not to mention more standard
aspects of economics.

00:37:10.130 --> 00:37:12.230
Let me lay out what I just said

00:37:12.230 --> 00:37:14.220
somewhat more analytically.

00:37:14.220 --> 00:37:16.793
We have here something called values.

00:37:18.620 --> 00:37:22.130
Which is here this,
sorry, social preferences.

00:37:22.130 --> 00:37:25.570
Suppose there's an
incentive maker, a designer,

00:37:25.570 --> 00:37:27.390
social planner, call 'em.

00:37:27.390 --> 00:37:29.900
And, she wants to affect the action

00:37:29.900 --> 00:37:32.270
the pro-social action on the right.

00:37:32.270 --> 00:37:35.500
She has some incentive
that she can impose.

00:37:35.500 --> 00:37:37.730
A tax or subsidy or something.

00:37:37.730 --> 00:37:40.160
That would affect the material payoffs.

00:37:40.160 --> 00:37:42.240
And that will have a positive effect

00:37:42.240 --> 00:37:44.970
on the right hand term pro-social action.

00:37:44.970 --> 00:37:47.340
The problem is that people
have social preferences

00:37:47.340 --> 00:37:50.040
which might have led them to
take the pro-social action

00:37:50.040 --> 00:37:51.393
anyway in the first place.

00:37:52.340 --> 00:37:53.970
And, that's not a problem.

00:37:53.970 --> 00:37:56.330
The problem is the arrow going downwards

00:37:56.330 --> 00:37:58.630
from incentive down to social preferences.

00:37:58.630 --> 00:38:00.880
If that arrow's negative
so that the incentive

00:38:00.880 --> 00:38:03.100
has a negative impact
on social preferences

00:38:03.100 --> 00:38:04.550
then you have a problem.

00:38:04.550 --> 00:38:09.550
So, let me lay out the total effect is,

00:38:10.530 --> 00:38:12.580
the direct effect, that's the top route

00:38:12.580 --> 00:38:15.700
going through the benefits and costs.

00:38:15.700 --> 00:38:18.220
The indirect effect is
the effect going from

00:38:18.220 --> 00:38:19.870
the incentive to the social preferences

00:38:19.870 --> 00:38:21.320
and to the pro-social action.

00:38:22.320 --> 00:38:25.413
Typically economics has
ignored the lower route.

00:38:26.550 --> 00:38:28.210
And in recent years we've found out

00:38:28.210 --> 00:38:30.023
that the lower route really matters.

00:38:31.390 --> 00:38:35.830
So, what I mean by separability is

00:38:35.830 --> 00:38:38.110
that the total is just the direct effect.

00:38:38.110 --> 00:38:40.390
There isn't any indirect effect.

00:38:40.390 --> 00:38:45.283
Now, empirically there's some bad news.

00:38:46.820 --> 00:38:51.820
The firemen in Boston in
2001 just before Christmas

00:38:54.930 --> 00:38:57.680
got a message from the fire commissioner

00:38:57.680 --> 00:39:01.000
who said that he'd noticed
that the people calling in sick

00:39:01.000 --> 00:39:02.730
tended to get sick on Mondays and Fridays

00:39:02.730 --> 00:39:04.740
and he found that very irritating.

00:39:04.740 --> 00:39:08.190
And so, until then they'd
had unlimited sick days.

00:39:08.190 --> 00:39:10.800
In fact, very few people
abused the sick days

00:39:10.800 --> 00:39:13.280
or at least very few people
abused them very much

00:39:13.280 --> 00:39:14.673
so they went up to 15.

00:39:15.550 --> 00:39:19.610
But the commissioner then said, as of now

00:39:19.610 --> 00:39:21.800
if you call in sick more
than 15 times a year

00:39:21.800 --> 00:39:22.800
your pay will be docked.

00:39:22.800 --> 00:39:24.173
So it's a penalty.

00:39:26.936 --> 00:39:28.380
And, what happened on
Christmas and New Years

00:39:28.380 --> 00:39:29.723
was the call ins doubled.

00:39:31.230 --> 00:39:32.810
And what happened in the next year

00:39:32.810 --> 00:39:35.350
was over the whole year
the number of people

00:39:35.350 --> 00:39:37.390
calling in sick doubled.

00:39:37.390 --> 00:39:39.763
And the firemen who were interviewed said,

00:39:40.640 --> 00:39:42.860
sorry, I go to work when I'm injured,

00:39:42.860 --> 00:39:44.300
I go to work when I'm sick.

00:39:44.300 --> 00:39:45.960
I do that because I'm a public servant

00:39:45.960 --> 00:39:46.860
and so on and so on.

00:39:46.860 --> 00:39:48.811
They felt insulted.

00:39:48.811 --> 00:39:51.410
And, so they just retaliated.

00:39:51.410 --> 00:39:53.760
That's what's called strong crowding out.

00:39:53.760 --> 00:39:57.100
That's when the incentive
not only blunts the effect

00:39:57.100 --> 00:39:58.660
but actually reverses it.

00:39:58.660 --> 00:40:00.530
Now Sandra Polania-Reyes and I,

00:40:00.530 --> 00:40:02.707
that's Sandra by the way in Bogata.

00:40:02.707 --> 00:40:03.840
She's from Columbia.

00:40:03.840 --> 00:40:05.450
She's doing an experiment in the streets

00:40:05.450 --> 00:40:07.140
among market people in Bogata.

00:40:07.140 --> 00:40:09.610
She's an fantastic experimental economist.

00:40:09.610 --> 00:40:11.667
We did a bunch of papers.

00:40:11.667 --> 00:40:15.080
In most of the experiments
of which we collected

00:40:15.080 --> 00:40:19.340
a large number, there was crowding out.

00:40:19.340 --> 00:40:23.920
So the incentive in economics
would be called a substitute

00:40:23.920 --> 00:40:25.130
for the morals.

00:40:25.130 --> 00:40:28.020
A substitute in economics
is the following,

00:40:28.020 --> 00:40:31.760
if an incentive and a moral
preference is a substitute

00:40:31.760 --> 00:40:33.310
then the higher the incentive

00:40:33.310 --> 00:40:35.960
the less is the effect
of social preferences.

00:40:35.960 --> 00:40:37.420
The larger one variable is

00:40:37.420 --> 00:40:40.000
the less is the derivative
of the outcome effect

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:40.833
with the other one.

00:40:40.833 --> 00:40:42.739
So that's what a substitute is.

00:40:42.739 --> 00:40:43.920
And that's what we found out.

00:40:43.920 --> 00:40:48.920
We did find out that in some
cases there was crowding in.

00:40:48.980 --> 00:40:50.690
And obviously in is gold.

00:40:50.690 --> 00:40:54.800
That's what the mechanism designer

00:40:54.800 --> 00:40:57.070
or social planner should be thinking of.

00:40:57.070 --> 00:41:00.740
Now, just to get a few words on the table.

00:41:00.740 --> 00:41:04.330
Wanna talk about the
nature of crowding out.

00:41:04.330 --> 00:41:06.550
It can be categorical.

00:41:06.550 --> 00:41:10.040
If there's an incentive
for something you'll say,

00:41:10.040 --> 00:41:11.070
it has an effect.

00:41:11.070 --> 00:41:12.700
Like, you know, he did it for the money.

00:41:12.700 --> 00:41:13.533
Well, how'd you know that?

00:41:13.533 --> 00:41:15.660
Well, there's some tax incentive
I don't know how big it is.

00:41:15.660 --> 00:41:17.940
That's a categorical effect.

00:41:17.940 --> 00:41:20.050
So, I wouldn't be as
likely to for example,

00:41:20.050 --> 00:41:23.180
give to the university if
there was some tax advantage

00:41:23.180 --> 00:41:25.380
because people might
discount my generosity.

00:41:26.423 --> 00:41:27.910
Now, the other is that there's,

00:41:27.910 --> 00:41:29.820
sorry, there's marginal crowding out,

00:41:29.820 --> 00:41:32.520
just means it depends on
how big the incentive is.

00:41:32.520 --> 00:41:34.600
And obviously you can
imagine psychologically

00:41:34.600 --> 00:41:35.670
both could be the case.

00:41:35.670 --> 00:41:37.260
And I'll tell you in two slides

00:41:37.260 --> 00:41:38.550
that we observe in experiments

00:41:38.550 --> 00:41:40.050
that both indeed are the case.

00:41:40.940 --> 00:41:43.990
And entirely different
dimension is the causes.

00:41:43.990 --> 00:41:45.850
Of which I think there are two.

00:41:45.850 --> 00:41:48.440
One I has to do with framing.

00:41:48.440 --> 00:41:50.420
That is, the incentive makes it

00:41:50.420 --> 00:41:52.880
a different kind of situation.

00:41:52.880 --> 00:41:54.300
So it doesn't change your preferences

00:41:54.300 --> 00:41:56.080
it just tells you, oh
this is like shopping

00:41:56.080 --> 00:41:58.480
and not like dealing with my family.

00:41:58.480 --> 00:41:59.313
So that's framing.

00:41:59.313 --> 00:42:02.020
It's called, situation
dependence in social psychology.

00:42:02.020 --> 00:42:04.550
Economist would call it state dependence.

00:42:04.550 --> 00:42:08.130
The states differ because in
one case there an incentive

00:42:08.130 --> 00:42:10.380
or an incentive of a particular size,

00:42:10.380 --> 00:42:12.490
and the other case there is no incentive.

00:42:12.490 --> 00:42:13.630
So those states differ

00:42:13.630 --> 00:42:16.600
and then we have state
dependent preferences.

00:42:16.600 --> 00:42:20.050
Finally, a consequence of
this crowding out phenomena

00:42:20.050 --> 00:42:23.080
is that the idea in economics

00:42:23.080 --> 00:42:25.140
is the way you implement and outcome.

00:42:25.140 --> 00:42:26.780
You have a some Nash equilibrium

00:42:26.780 --> 00:42:30.360
which is somehow not okay,
and you wanna change it.

00:42:30.360 --> 00:42:31.300
Well, what do you do?

00:42:31.300 --> 00:42:34.660
Well, you change the situation
so there's Nash equilibrium

00:42:34.660 --> 00:42:36.650
which has the desirable features.

00:42:36.650 --> 00:42:38.310
That's called, in mechanism design,

00:42:38.310 --> 00:42:40.700
implementation by Nash equilibrium.

00:42:40.700 --> 00:42:42.490
So the idea of the game is
to shift the equilibrium

00:42:42.490 --> 00:42:44.570
and it's a very good idea

00:42:44.570 --> 00:42:45.990
'cause when you're shifting,

00:42:45.990 --> 00:42:47.130
if you wanna shift an outcome

00:42:47.130 --> 00:42:49.210
you better make sure that
the desirable outcome

00:42:49.210 --> 00:42:51.500
you're trying to get is
actually a Nash equilibrium

00:42:51.500 --> 00:42:54.440
otherwise it will be
undone by private actions

00:42:54.440 --> 00:42:55.860
and the policy will fail.

00:42:55.860 --> 00:42:57.230
That's not a bad idea.

00:42:57.230 --> 00:43:02.230
But, we have to make sure
that that new Nash equilibrium

00:43:02.730 --> 00:43:06.140
that were desiring actually
reproduces the preferences

00:43:06.140 --> 00:43:08.030
of which support the equilibrium.

00:43:08.030 --> 00:43:09.940
So, we have a rather unusual concept.

00:43:09.940 --> 00:43:13.110
Remember where you heard it
first, equilibrium preferences.

00:43:13.110 --> 00:43:14.000
Okay.

00:43:14.000 --> 00:43:17.040
What it means is what has to be stationary

00:43:17.040 --> 00:43:19.360
for a policy outcome to be the expectation

00:43:19.360 --> 00:43:21.410
that you get by implementing a policy

00:43:21.410 --> 00:43:24.020
is that given the preferences

00:43:24.020 --> 00:43:26.140
which will result from these incentives,

00:43:26.140 --> 00:43:27.830
the outcome that you want will actually

00:43:27.830 --> 00:43:29.480
be implemented by private action.

00:43:30.550 --> 00:43:33.210
So, and this is the analogy

00:43:33.210 --> 00:43:35.433
to the so called, Lucas critique.

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:38.753
Now, let's look at some data.

00:43:40.570 --> 00:43:42.210
This is an experiment,

00:43:42.210 --> 00:43:44.870
this is a state dependent
preferences subject

00:43:44.870 --> 00:43:46.430
both categorical and marginal.

00:43:46.430 --> 00:43:47.410
You're just using the terms

00:43:47.410 --> 00:43:49.030
I just introduced in the last slide.

00:43:49.030 --> 00:43:52.060
It's a wonderful experiment
with a public goods game.

00:43:52.060 --> 00:43:53.660
I won't describe the details of the game

00:43:53.660 --> 00:43:57.210
but the public goods game is
in person prisoners dilemma

00:43:57.210 --> 00:44:00.560
in which the dominant
strategy is not to contribute.

00:44:00.560 --> 00:44:02.410
Self interested person
would not contribute

00:44:02.410 --> 00:44:04.520
everybody else should contribute.

00:44:04.520 --> 00:44:08.749
And so, no sorry, in this game

00:44:08.749 --> 00:44:12.180
the strategy of a purely selfish person

00:44:12.180 --> 00:44:14.210
the person's own benefit
from the public good

00:44:14.210 --> 00:44:17.560
would motivate them contributing 25.

00:44:17.560 --> 00:44:21.670
So, there are, there is

00:44:21.670 --> 00:44:23.640
here there's no incentive.

00:44:23.640 --> 00:44:26.500
Here there's an incentive
of 12 and that's 60.

00:44:26.500 --> 00:44:28.100
This is just, you get an incentive

00:44:28.100 --> 00:44:29.600
if you're a hight contributor.

00:44:30.576 --> 00:44:33.553
So this is all played
anonymously with real money.

00:44:34.780 --> 00:44:36.730
Let's look at the red dots here.

00:44:36.730 --> 00:44:39.350
That's what a selfish
person would contribute

00:44:39.350 --> 00:44:40.720
with no incentive.

00:44:40.720 --> 00:44:44.050
If you add the incentive then
they would contribute more

00:44:44.050 --> 00:44:45.533
if they're totally selfish.

00:44:46.670 --> 00:44:49.290
And then, if you have a big incentive

00:44:49.290 --> 00:44:50.640
they contribute a lot more.

00:44:51.630 --> 00:44:53.450
So that's what a selfish person would do.

00:44:53.450 --> 00:44:55.030
Now let's look at what people actually did

00:44:55.030 --> 00:44:55.930
in the experiment.

00:44:56.830 --> 00:44:59.900
With no incentive they
contributed a lot more than 25.

00:44:59.900 --> 00:45:01.530
They contributed 37.

00:45:01.530 --> 00:45:05.280
This distance here is a measure
of their social preferences

00:45:05.280 --> 00:45:08.650
or their ethical desire to
contribute to the public good.

00:45:08.650 --> 00:45:11.400
And when you add the incentive
sure enough it goes up.

00:45:11.400 --> 00:45:14.060
It goes up from 37 to 38.

00:45:14.060 --> 00:45:15.040
So if you just looked at that

00:45:15.040 --> 00:45:17.230
you'd say the incentive worked.

00:45:17.230 --> 00:45:19.170
But now look at this.

00:45:19.170 --> 00:45:21.173
If it goes up to 60,

00:45:22.490 --> 00:45:23.383
what do you got?

00:45:24.260 --> 00:45:27.310
There's no effect at all
of the social preferences.

00:45:27.310 --> 00:45:29.630
Those two numbers out there
obviously, statistically

00:45:29.630 --> 00:45:31.350
and significantly different.

00:45:31.350 --> 00:45:34.330
So, these individuals with no incentives

00:45:34.330 --> 00:45:38.470
made a very major commitment
to the social good

00:45:38.470 --> 00:45:42.430
which they didn't do at all
when there were incentives.

00:45:42.430 --> 00:45:45.210
And the difference is, as you
can see, were quite large.

00:45:45.210 --> 00:45:46.970
That's crowding out.

00:45:46.970 --> 00:45:48.710
Now, is it marginal crowding out

00:45:48.710 --> 00:45:50.900
or categorical crowding out?

00:45:50.900 --> 00:45:53.640
Well, to do that what I did is

00:45:53.640 --> 00:45:57.120
well, I said, well, suppose
that there was a incentive

00:45:57.120 --> 00:45:59.620
of epsilon, a small number,

00:45:59.620 --> 00:46:02.010
and that would be somewhere right here,

00:46:02.010 --> 00:46:03.790
right near the vertical axis.

00:46:03.790 --> 00:46:05.330
How much would they have contributed?

00:46:05.330 --> 00:46:08.740
Well, I just projected this
line from that purple dot

00:46:08.740 --> 00:46:10.670
that's what they did with
that incentive to that.

00:46:10.670 --> 00:46:13.210
And then back to here and said,

00:46:13.210 --> 00:46:14.760
that's roughly what
they would've considered

00:46:14.760 --> 00:46:17.803
if you had a vanishingly small
incentive but it was there.

00:46:18.760 --> 00:46:21.143
And, that gives you 34.

00:46:23.170 --> 00:46:26.173
And, now notice this says that,

00:46:27.056 --> 00:46:29.983
this is a categorical crowding out.

00:46:30.890 --> 00:46:33.040
The fact that this line is flatter

00:46:33.040 --> 00:46:36.220
means that varying the
incentive has less affect.

00:46:36.220 --> 00:46:37.780
That's marginal crowding out.

00:46:37.780 --> 00:46:39.570
So both were going on.

00:46:39.570 --> 00:46:42.230
And you know, both were quite substantial.

00:46:42.230 --> 00:46:44.550
And when Sandra and I did this

00:46:44.550 --> 00:46:46.190
in lots of different experiments,

00:46:46.190 --> 00:46:48.950
it turns out that almost
always you get both effects.

00:46:48.950 --> 00:46:50.623
It's quite surprising.

00:46:52.510 --> 00:46:54.030
Okay, now let's turn,

00:46:54.030 --> 00:46:55.910
this is the kind of information,

00:46:55.910 --> 00:46:58.130
you know, when people say,
okay how do you use this

00:46:58.130 --> 00:46:59.630
to design policy?

00:46:59.630 --> 00:47:02.360
Well, I think a combination of
looking at these experiments

00:47:02.360 --> 00:47:06.110
and also looking at what social
psychologist already know

00:47:06.110 --> 00:47:09.970
about why crowding out
occurs, will help us.

00:47:09.970 --> 00:47:11.240
This is from Mark Lepper,

00:47:11.240 --> 00:47:13.020
whose work I admire very much.

00:47:13.020 --> 00:47:14.220
That's the social planner.

00:47:14.220 --> 00:47:16.230
Suggests how complicated his,

00:47:16.230 --> 00:47:18.620
I guess his in that case, task is.

00:47:18.620 --> 00:47:21.427
Lepper says this, "The
multiple social meanings

00:47:21.427 --> 00:47:22.887
"of the use of tangible rewards

00:47:22.887 --> 00:47:25.107
"are reflected in our
everyday distinctions between

00:47:25.107 --> 00:47:28.817
"bribes and bonuses,
incentives and salaries.

00:47:28.817 --> 00:47:31.987
"They carry different connotations
concerning, for example,

00:47:31.987 --> 00:47:34.917
"the likely conditions under
which the reward was offered,

00:47:34.917 --> 00:47:37.157
"the presumed motives of the person

00:47:37.157 --> 00:47:38.697
"administering the reward,

00:47:38.697 --> 00:47:40.267
"and the relationship between the agent

00:47:40.267 --> 00:47:41.660
"and the recipient of the reward."

00:47:41.660 --> 00:47:42.860
Yes, that's sound right.

00:47:42.860 --> 00:47:44.150
That sounds like something economists

00:47:44.150 --> 00:47:45.640
should pay attention to.

00:47:45.640 --> 00:47:50.023
So let's look at some actual policies.

00:47:52.760 --> 00:47:55.060
We have rural Colombians

00:47:55.060 --> 00:47:58.223
and they're playing a public goods game.

00:47:59.780 --> 00:48:03.550
And, these are real rural
people, not students.

00:48:03.550 --> 00:48:05.232
And the game was designed to look like

00:48:05.232 --> 00:48:07.700
how much stuff are you
taking out of the forest.

00:48:07.700 --> 00:48:09.610
'Cause they were deforesting a place.

00:48:09.610 --> 00:48:12.930
This was an experiment
by Juan Camilla Cardenas

00:48:12.930 --> 00:48:15.050
who intervened there in Columbia

00:48:15.050 --> 00:48:16.698
before he became a grad student.

00:48:16.698 --> 00:48:18.330
He only found out later

00:48:18.330 --> 00:48:19.650
that he could publish papers on this.

00:48:19.650 --> 00:48:22.620
He was trying to change
whether people could cooperate

00:48:22.620 --> 00:48:24.150
and not deforest the place.

00:48:24.150 --> 00:48:26.920
When he came to grad school he
got a couple of publications

00:48:26.920 --> 00:48:28.530
from stuff that he was doing primarily

00:48:28.530 --> 00:48:30.210
'cause he was community organizer.

00:48:30.210 --> 00:48:31.173
Which is very nice.

00:48:33.520 --> 00:48:36.840
If you look here, or there,

00:48:36.840 --> 00:48:39.420
this is the first, this the game played

00:48:39.420 --> 00:48:43.920
and they, what the vertical axis is,

00:48:43.920 --> 00:48:45.570
how far did they deviate

00:48:45.570 --> 00:48:48.140
from what a selfish person would do?

00:48:48.140 --> 00:48:51.070
Now, the ideal for all of the society

00:48:51.070 --> 00:48:52.883
would be deviated by six.

00:48:54.050 --> 00:48:55.720
And, an entirely selfish person

00:48:55.720 --> 00:48:57.780
would've deviated not at all.

00:48:57.780 --> 00:48:59.610
And so they were kind of in between.

00:48:59.610 --> 00:49:01.530
So this says round after round

00:49:01.530 --> 00:49:03.240
they are kind of halfway between being

00:49:03.240 --> 00:49:05.190
the sinner and the saint.

00:49:05.190 --> 00:49:07.430
Then he stops the game here and he says,

00:49:07.430 --> 00:49:10.260
okay, the groups that's black

00:49:10.260 --> 00:49:12.540
are gonna be subjected to a fined

00:49:12.540 --> 00:49:13.730
if they take out too much.

00:49:13.730 --> 00:49:15.700
They'll be monitored and
if they're discovered

00:49:15.700 --> 00:49:17.840
to have taken out too
much they'll be fined.

00:49:17.840 --> 00:49:19.720
The group that's red are gonna be allowed

00:49:19.720 --> 00:49:22.270
to communicate with each other verbally,

00:49:22.270 --> 00:49:25.810
and then after that the
game is played anonymously.

00:49:25.810 --> 00:49:27.440
So, you see what happened here

00:49:27.440 --> 00:49:32.340
at first the fine worked exactly.

00:49:32.340 --> 00:49:34.680
They exactly implemented
the social optimum

00:49:34.680 --> 00:49:38.530
which is to deviate six from
what a selfish person would do.

00:49:38.530 --> 00:49:41.013
And as time with on they
went right down to zero.

00:49:41.940 --> 00:49:43.290
The fine wasn't big enough.

00:49:44.910 --> 00:49:48.300
So essentially, these people who had acted

00:49:48.300 --> 00:49:51.480
halfway between being selfish
and being completely generous

00:49:51.480 --> 00:49:54.450
ended up after eight rounds
being entirely selfish.

00:49:54.450 --> 00:49:57.370
Sounds a little like
the previous experiment.

00:49:57.370 --> 00:50:00.420
The ones who communicated
did a little better.

00:50:00.420 --> 00:50:02.870
These red dots here are a
little better than those.

00:50:02.870 --> 00:50:06.540
They did surprisingly not well to me.

00:50:06.540 --> 00:50:08.217
It was class divided society

00:50:08.217 --> 00:50:10.450
and these groups were of different classes

00:50:10.450 --> 00:50:12.000
and they didn't communicate very well.

00:50:12.000 --> 00:50:14.323
There's some great stories
I could tell you about that.

00:50:15.240 --> 00:50:20.240
But, I think the best
way of explaining this is

00:50:20.400 --> 00:50:23.080
once the fine was announced people engaged

00:50:23.080 --> 00:50:26.120
in what psychologist
call moral disengagement.

00:50:26.120 --> 00:50:28.470
They just thought, oh
it's not a moral problem.

00:50:29.980 --> 00:50:33.040
They're fining us so not playing the game

00:50:33.040 --> 00:50:34.500
in a publicly responsible way

00:50:34.500 --> 00:50:38.123
is a commodity which I can
buy despite paying the price.

00:50:39.040 --> 00:50:41.083
Here's another experiment.

00:50:42.350 --> 00:50:44.140
This is a trust game.

00:50:44.140 --> 00:50:45.860
In the trust game there are two parties,

00:50:45.860 --> 00:50:49.230
the first party gets a sum of money

00:50:49.230 --> 00:50:52.113
which he or she then can
allocate to the second party.

00:50:53.210 --> 00:50:56.410
Before it gets to the second
party it's triples in amount.

00:50:56.410 --> 00:50:58.320
And the person who gets the tripled amount

00:50:58.320 --> 00:51:01.370
then can send some back
to the first person.

00:51:01.370 --> 00:51:02.420
It's like an investment.

00:51:02.420 --> 00:51:03.730
You invest in the second person

00:51:03.730 --> 00:51:05.080
and they give you some stuff back.

00:51:05.080 --> 00:51:07.040
But, there's no way of enforcing it.

00:51:07.040 --> 00:51:09.210
Well, you don't have to
be a genius at game theory

00:51:09.210 --> 00:51:11.530
to figure out that if you
thought the other person

00:51:11.530 --> 00:51:13.800
was entirely selfish
you should send nothing

00:51:13.800 --> 00:51:15.160
'cause they won't send it back anyway.

00:51:15.160 --> 00:51:17.820
So, that's the way the
game should be played.

00:51:17.820 --> 00:51:20.480
That's not the way the
game is played hardly ever.

00:51:20.480 --> 00:51:23.320
People send a lot and they
get a lot reciprocated.

00:51:23.320 --> 00:51:26.470
And if they send more
they get a lot more back.

00:51:26.470 --> 00:51:31.150
So, if we look at just the gray bars,

00:51:31.150 --> 00:51:34.260
the gray bar says that if
you send between two and four

00:51:34.260 --> 00:51:36.530
you get on average four back.

00:51:36.530 --> 00:51:38.130
If you send between five and seven

00:51:38.130 --> 00:51:39.880
you get a little over six back.

00:51:39.880 --> 00:51:42.350
So essentially the more you
send the more they send back.

00:51:42.350 --> 00:51:44.240
Though they don't have
to send back anything.

00:51:44.240 --> 00:51:45.290
So people are reciprocal.

00:51:45.290 --> 00:51:47.290
They respond to that signal.

00:51:47.290 --> 00:51:50.330
But then the experimenters
did a very clever thing.

00:51:50.330 --> 00:51:52.580
They gave the sender, the first person,

00:51:52.580 --> 00:51:54.470
the option to impose a fine.

00:51:54.470 --> 00:51:56.760
So, I can send a message to you saying,

00:51:56.760 --> 00:51:59.830
I'm sending you five and
if you don't send me back

00:51:59.830 --> 00:52:02.040
at least 10, remember
the thing is tripled,

00:52:02.040 --> 00:52:03.890
if you don't send me back at least 10,

00:52:03.890 --> 00:52:05.090
then I'm gonna fine you.

00:52:06.400 --> 00:52:08.093
And so,

00:52:10.274 --> 00:52:13.770
when the fine was imposed here,

00:52:13.770 --> 00:52:16.770
the black bars, that's what happens.

00:52:16.770 --> 00:52:18.540
Now look at the black bars.

00:52:18.540 --> 00:52:20.210
What do they tell you?

00:52:20.210 --> 00:52:22.290
Much less reciprocity.

00:52:22.290 --> 00:52:23.663
They're not reciprocating.

00:52:24.570 --> 00:52:28.200
So imposing the fine should
improve the situation

00:52:28.200 --> 00:52:29.410
'cause you're improving the incentives

00:52:29.410 --> 00:52:31.650
that's what economist
are always trying to do

00:52:31.650 --> 00:52:34.150
to get the thing closer
to a complete contract.

00:52:34.150 --> 00:52:37.070
But the closer you got,
the farther people came

00:52:37.070 --> 00:52:38.470
from the thing which would maximize

00:52:38.470 --> 00:52:40.800
the wellbeing of the two summed.

00:52:40.800 --> 00:52:43.820
But then, and even cleverer
move with the experiments

00:52:43.820 --> 00:52:45.206
gave the option to say,

00:52:45.206 --> 00:52:48.240
you can impose a fine
but you can publicly say

00:52:48.240 --> 00:52:49.970
I'm not imposing it.

00:52:49.970 --> 00:52:51.450
So here's five.

00:52:51.450 --> 00:52:54.140
I can impose a fine but I'm
not gonna impose a fine.

00:52:54.140 --> 00:52:54.973
And then what happens?

00:52:54.973 --> 00:52:56.350
Look at the white bars.

00:52:56.350 --> 00:52:57.710
That's what happens.

00:52:57.710 --> 00:52:59.550
Now, why did that change?

00:52:59.550 --> 00:53:01.390
And, what changed?

00:53:01.390 --> 00:53:04.500
The fact that fine was possible
but you didn't impose it

00:53:04.500 --> 00:53:05.880
allowed you the first person

00:53:05.880 --> 00:53:08.550
to signal to the other
person, I trust you.

00:53:08.550 --> 00:53:12.570
It said, I'm not tryna
get the most out of you.

00:53:12.570 --> 00:53:16.130
So, it was, this tells us something

00:53:16.130 --> 00:53:17.870
about designing institutions.

00:53:17.870 --> 00:53:20.950
A little change like that
allowed a piece of information

00:53:20.950 --> 00:53:23.013
to transmitted in a truthful way.

