We never use the word
punishment of course.

01:02:29.700 --> 01:02:32.170
We just say, you can
pay to reduce the fining

01:02:32.170 --> 01:02:33.053
of somebody else.

01:02:34.180 --> 01:02:37.383
So, they start off a little
higher and it goes up.

01:02:38.490 --> 01:02:41.700
Now what happens in here,
those places there is,

01:02:41.700 --> 01:02:43.180
there were a lot of people
not contributing much

01:02:43.180 --> 01:02:45.190
and people were punishing.

01:02:45.190 --> 01:02:47.040
By the end of the game
everybody contributing a lot

01:02:47.040 --> 01:02:48.940
and nobody's punishing.

01:02:48.940 --> 01:02:51.470
Now notice, that's a very
small change in the rules.

01:02:51.470 --> 01:02:54.070
That had a huge impact.

01:02:54.070 --> 01:02:57.470
Here, there were a few selfish people

01:02:57.470 --> 01:02:58.930
who were driving this downwards

01:02:58.930 --> 01:03:00.410
because the ones who were,

01:03:00.410 --> 01:03:02.380
would've liked to contribute
were getting angry

01:03:02.380 --> 01:03:04.120
'cause the other people
weren't contributing.

01:03:04.120 --> 01:03:07.220
Over here, possibly a
small number of people

01:03:07.220 --> 01:03:08.190
who are civic minded

01:03:08.190 --> 01:03:10.120
and willing to actually punish the others,

01:03:10.120 --> 01:03:11.623
were driving the equilibrium.

01:03:12.550 --> 01:03:15.173
Now, there's a wonderful
puzzle here by the way.

01:03:16.230 --> 01:03:18.780
This game here is a public goods game

01:03:18.780 --> 01:03:21.650
in which the dominant
strategy is to not contribute.

01:03:21.650 --> 01:03:23.570
That means, whatever anyone else does

01:03:23.570 --> 01:03:25.780
what you should do if you're
maximizing yourself interest

01:03:25.780 --> 01:03:26.683
is don't give.

01:03:28.250 --> 01:03:31.760
This game over here, the punishment game,

01:03:31.760 --> 01:03:33.139
it's the same game.

01:03:33.139 --> 01:03:34.890
Punishment's a public good.

01:03:34.890 --> 01:03:36.450
The dominant strategy about punishing

01:03:36.450 --> 01:03:37.870
is you shouldn't punish.

01:03:37.870 --> 01:03:39.253
Let somebody else punish.

01:03:40.110 --> 01:03:42.700
So, in the second round
people should've been

01:03:42.700 --> 01:03:44.720
as selfish as the first.

01:03:44.720 --> 01:03:46.790
It's a very interesting characteristic.

01:03:46.790 --> 01:03:48.630
And I think they're good
evolutionary reasons

01:03:48.630 --> 01:03:49.770
why we have this.

01:03:49.770 --> 01:03:52.130
That people here were acting selfish

01:03:52.130 --> 01:03:54.560
but when it came to
ability to punish people

01:03:54.560 --> 01:03:55.393
who were breaking rules,

01:03:55.393 --> 01:03:57.950
people are very happy to participate.

01:03:57.950 --> 01:03:59.390
It would take us somewhat farer field

01:03:59.390 --> 01:04:02.143
to explain why that would
be true evolutionarily.

01:04:05.150 --> 01:04:08.230
If you compare these two games
with which you're familiar

01:04:08.230 --> 01:04:09.770
the top one I just described.

01:04:09.770 --> 01:04:12.970
And this was the one
in which the incentives

01:04:12.970 --> 01:04:15.253
drove out reciprocity.

01:04:16.310 --> 01:04:17.173
So that's a contrast, right?

01:04:17.173 --> 01:04:19.830
In once case fining people over here,

01:04:19.830 --> 01:04:23.150
fining people was leading
people to contribute more.

01:04:23.150 --> 01:04:24.850
They didn't contribute
less when they got fined

01:04:24.850 --> 01:04:26.670
they contributed more.

01:04:26.670 --> 01:04:28.200
And in the lower one,

01:04:28.200 --> 01:04:30.840
the prospect of a fine made
people less reciprocal.

01:04:30.840 --> 01:04:32.560
So in one case it seemed to be building up

01:04:32.560 --> 01:04:34.030
social preferences, the top.

01:04:34.030 --> 01:04:35.750
And the other case not.

01:04:35.750 --> 01:04:38.800
Well, I was able to look into

01:04:38.800 --> 01:04:41.090
why this experiment
worked out the way it was.

01:04:41.090 --> 01:04:43.110
Remember, I can give you five

01:04:43.110 --> 01:04:45.570
and then I can say I want
seven and a half back

01:04:45.570 --> 01:04:47.070
then we'd split the total.

01:04:47.070 --> 01:04:48.360
Or, I could say I want 10 back

01:04:48.360 --> 01:04:50.520
then I'd get most the total, right?

01:04:50.520 --> 01:04:52.670
The ones who were greedy were the ones

01:04:52.670 --> 01:04:55.450
who were being negatively responded to.

01:04:55.450 --> 01:04:58.950
So, the negative response was
not a response to incentives.

01:04:58.950 --> 01:05:00.910
It a response to greed.

01:05:00.910 --> 01:05:02.870
The ones who were saying I'll fine you

01:05:02.870 --> 01:05:04.690
if you don't split it 50-50 with me

01:05:04.690 --> 01:05:06.520
were not negatively affected.

01:05:06.520 --> 01:05:07.353
So there's a lesson there.

01:05:07.353 --> 01:05:09.113
That it's not the incentive per se.

