01:08:41.470 --> 01:08:46.470
Now, the economy and society
into which we're now entering

01:08:48.220 --> 01:08:51.330
couldn't be farther from
the world of James Buchanan

01:08:51.330 --> 01:08:53.163
dealing with his fruit seller.

01:08:54.350 --> 01:08:56.970
We're not living in a
world in which we agree

01:08:56.970 --> 01:08:59.230
on the property rights being transacted.

01:08:59.230 --> 01:09:00.530
We're not living in a world in which

01:09:00.530 --> 01:09:02.890
everything that matters,
that goes on between us,

01:09:02.890 --> 01:09:06.310
is covered by a costlessly
enforceable contract.

01:09:06.310 --> 01:09:09.430
Whether it's secondhand
smoke, or climate change,

01:09:09.430 --> 01:09:12.320
or epidemic spread, or hiring a worker,

01:09:12.320 --> 01:09:15.350
or giving a loan, or a taking a loan.

01:09:15.350 --> 01:09:20.350
And so, think of the 18th, 19th century.

01:09:20.900 --> 01:09:23.180
The sinews that connected
the world was trade,

01:09:23.180 --> 01:09:24.800
and grain, and steel.

01:09:24.800 --> 01:09:26.500
That's not what connects us today.

01:09:27.660 --> 01:09:31.930
We do that, but it's also
sneezes and burning carbon.

01:09:31.930 --> 01:09:34.280
And all kind of other things.

01:09:34.280 --> 01:09:36.403
That will never be subject to contract.

01:09:37.300 --> 01:09:42.250
So, obviously, the
economist's job until now

01:09:42.250 --> 01:09:44.100
