01:27:03.700 --> 01:27:06.050
That's knowledge base, that's affect,

01:27:06.050 --> 01:27:07.660
that' caring for people.

01:27:07.660 --> 01:27:09.760
The knowledge and caring based economy

01:27:09.760 --> 01:27:12.130
is a lot more like the
hunter-gather economy

01:27:12.130 --> 01:27:13.900
than it was like the economy

01:27:13.900 --> 01:27:15.740
of Buchanan and his fruit stand.

01:27:15.740 --> 01:27:18.990
So, we may be able to
learn a lesson from that.

01:27:18.990 --> 01:27:21.780
Obviously, given the modern
communication abilities,

01:27:21.780 --> 01:27:23.590
given also modern states,

01:27:23.590 --> 01:27:25.630
the modern means of coercion and so on,

01:27:25.630 --> 01:27:27.320
it's an entirely new world.

01:27:27.320 --> 01:27:29.810
I'm not suggesting we
can model our society

01:27:29.810 --> 01:27:32.340
on a sorta modern day Flintstone economy

01:27:32.340 --> 01:27:33.990
but we do have something to learn

01:27:33.990 --> 01:27:38.490
about our capacities to cooperate
are really extraordinary.

01:27:38.490 --> 01:27:39.323
And,

01:27:42.220 --> 01:27:44.340
if you look at human
institution that have been

01:27:44.340 --> 01:27:46.850
a big success, the cooperative

01:27:46.850 --> 01:27:51.230
and egalitarian hunter-gather
society is far and away

01:27:51.230 --> 01:27:52.690
the most successful.

01:27:52.690 --> 01:27:55.220
Enduring for 100 thousand years.

01:27:55.220 --> 01:27:57.373
Capitalism is just a few centuries old.

01:27:58.390 --> 01:28:01.850
And, I think we may be moving
into an economic situation

01:28:01.850 --> 01:28:05.120
in which, if can quote
Kenneth Arrow again,

01:28:05.120 --> 01:28:06.370
it wasn't on the slide.

01:28:06.370 --> 01:28:10.157
Arrow said, "Information, knowledge,

01:28:10.157 --> 01:28:12.577
"is a fugitive resource.

01:28:12.577 --> 01:28:13.790
"It runs away."

01:28:13.790 --> 01:28:15.290
Just like that animals who ran away

01:28:15.290 --> 01:28:16.670
from the hunters and gatherers.

01:28:16.670 --> 01:28:18.040
You cannot own it.

01:28:18.040 --> 01:28:20.030
He said we're just beginning to understand

01:28:20.030 --> 01:28:23.340
the contradiction between
fundamental economics

01:28:23.340 --> 01:28:24.593
and property rights.

01:28:25.800 --> 01:28:29.460
So he was talking, and
this was three decades ago,

01:28:29.460 --> 01:28:32.290
Arrow was talking about
a fundamental problem

01:28:32.290 --> 01:28:34.110
about moving into an economy in which

01:28:34.110 --> 01:28:36.560
it's not possible to own stuff.

01:28:36.560 --> 01:28:39.390
And when you try to own it with
intellectual property rights

01:28:39.390 --> 01:28:42.060
it's actually dysfunctional for society.

01:28:42.060 --> 01:28:44.850
We're moving into a society in
which those rules don't work.

01:28:44.850 --> 01:28:47.220
And so, Arrow was saying,
three decades ago,

01:28:47.220 --> 01:28:49.270
we're gonna have fundamental
institutional changes

01:28:49.270 --> 01:28:51.840
because the stuff the
economy is now made of

01:28:51.840 --> 01:28:54.310
doesn't work anymore for
this private property

01:28:54.310 --> 01:28:57.320
and complete contracting regime.

01:28:57.320 --> 01:28:58.153
Now, I don't think it means

01:28:58.153 --> 01:28:59.850
we're gonna do away with private property.

01:28:59.850 --> 01:29:00.790
And I certainly don't think

01:29:00.790 --> 01:29:02.670
we're gonna do away with
contracts in markets.

01:29:02.670 --> 01:29:05.050
It means it'll play a
much more limited role

01:29:05.050 --> 01:29:06.370
and we better find out some way

01:29:06.370 --> 01:29:07.670
to deal with the other stuff.

01:29:07.670 --> 01:29:10.550
Whether it's intrinsic motivation, trust,

01:29:10.550 --> 01:29:13.190
morality, and other things.

01:29:13.190 --> 01:29:15.820
Arrow didn't say what they might be.

01:29:15.820 --> 01:29:19.310
- [Man] Hi, do you have
a stance on whether

01:29:19.310 --> 01:29:22.570
we should use public policy
to foster social norms?

01:29:22.570 --> 01:29:27.570
For one point, it's clear
that some norms are universal,

01:29:29.233 --> 01:29:33.740
say, trustness and being
generous and so on.

01:29:33.740 --> 01:29:35.840
But saying fostering egalitarian norms

01:29:35.840 --> 01:29:37.490
would be much more controversial.

01:29:40.000 --> 01:29:44.670
- I think, this is a
very difficult question.

01:29:44.670 --> 01:29:46.080
Having listened to my lecture

01:29:46.080 --> 01:29:49.320
it's a question which
absolutely has to be asked.

01:29:49.320 --> 01:29:51.690
If you take the Aristotelian position

01:29:51.690 --> 01:29:53.410
you must also then say,

01:29:53.410 --> 01:29:55.810
what would it mean to be a good citizen?

01:29:55.810 --> 01:30:00.770
Now, there's an easy way
to answer the question

01:30:00.770 --> 01:30:05.770
which is, States today are
engaged in inculcating norms.

01:30:06.540 --> 01:30:08.970
They do it in schools, they
do it through patriotism,

01:30:08.970 --> 01:30:10.970
they do it through political
leadership and so on.

01:30:10.970 --> 01:30:13.450
It goes on all the time.

01:30:13.450 --> 01:30:15.630
So, I could say at a minimum,

01:30:15.630 --> 01:30:16.820
what I would like us to do

01:30:16.820 --> 01:30:19.670
is have a public discussion
about which norms

01:30:19.670 --> 01:30:22.800
we would like to see brought to the fore.

01:30:22.800 --> 01:30:27.190
Now, if you have a
reliably democratic society

01:30:27.190 --> 01:30:30.080
in which sincere communication and debate

01:30:30.080 --> 01:30:31.960
following Habermas for example,

01:30:31.960 --> 01:30:33.690
as a philosophical principle,

01:30:33.690 --> 01:30:35.570
you can see that might be a frame work

01:30:35.570 --> 01:30:37.560
in which we can then have some confidence

01:30:37.560 --> 01:30:40.613
in the kinds of norms
that would inculcated.

01:30:41.720 --> 01:30:43.193
I don't think we have any reason to think

01:30:43.193 --> 01:30:44.900
that that's gonna solve the problem.

01:30:44.900 --> 01:30:46.530
And think there's a lot to fear from it.

01:30:46.530 --> 01:30:48.780
For example, I think one of the things,

01:30:48.780 --> 01:30:52.340
I think human beings are
generous and also very

01:30:52.340 --> 01:30:55.520
given to us and them distinctions, both.

01:30:55.520 --> 01:30:57.100
We're generous towards the us

01:30:57.100 --> 01:30:59.130
and we're often indifferent
towards the them.

01:30:59.130 --> 01:31:01.183
I think we evolved that way genetically.

01:31:02.225 --> 01:31:05.390
I worked on that for a
long time in biology.

01:31:05.390 --> 01:31:07.690
I think there's a very good
case that that's who we are.

01:31:07.690 --> 01:31:10.250
If that's true, that's a problem.

01:31:10.250 --> 01:31:12.924
Because, we'd like to
inculcate the altruistic

01:31:12.924 --> 01:31:16.140
and common norms, and
we'd like in most cases,

01:31:16.140 --> 01:31:17.900
not all, but in many cases,

01:31:17.900 --> 01:31:21.540
to obliterate those repugnant
us and them distinctions

01:31:21.540 --> 01:31:24.040
which work to the
disadvantage of less well of

01:31:24.040 --> 01:31:27.425
and people of other groups.

01:31:27.425 --> 01:31:29.030
I don't know how that can be done.

01:31:29.030 --> 01:31:30.650
I don't think it can be avoided.

01:31:30.650 --> 01:31:35.650
And I think that the idea
that this is going on anyway

01:31:36.860 --> 01:31:39.690
without an open discussion
about the people

01:31:39.690 --> 01:31:42.060
we would like to be, and I mean globally,

01:31:42.060 --> 01:31:44.020
that's certainly a problem.

01:31:44.020 --> 01:31:46.660
Whether or not bringing
that discussion to the fore

01:31:46.660 --> 01:31:50.190
would address the problem and
address all the possibilities

01:31:50.190 --> 01:31:52.220
of norms which would come to the fore

01:31:52.220 --> 01:31:55.300
in that discussion might
be racist, or homophobic,

01:31:55.300 --> 01:31:57.083
or other repugnant things.

01:31:58.110 --> 01:31:59.943
That, of course we can't know.

01:32:01.110 --> 01:32:02.710
But thank you for your question.

01:32:04.000 --> 01:32:05.433
Are you from economics?

01:32:05.433 --> 01:32:06.266
- [Man] Yes.

01:32:06.266 --> 01:32:08.312
- Don't write your
dissertation on that one.

01:32:08.312 --> 01:32:09.520
(crowd laughing)

01:32:09.520 --> 01:32:11.270
Unless you have a really good idea.

01:32:14.420 --> 01:32:17.650
No, by the way, a brilliant dissertation

01:32:17.650 --> 01:32:20.870
was written in Harvard in the mid-60s

01:32:20.870 --> 01:32:24.710
by Herbert Gintus on
endogenous preferences.

01:32:24.710 --> 01:32:27.400
And you might go and
find it it was a very,

01:32:27.400 --> 01:32:29.360
Amartya Sen was on his committee.

01:32:29.360 --> 01:32:31.250
But, have a look.

01:32:31.250 --> 01:32:33.580
Some people have gotten away
with writing dissertations

01:32:33.580 --> 01:32:36.040
about really big questions
like the one you asked me.

01:32:36.040 --> 01:32:39.410
But as I say, (chuckles)

01:32:39.410 --> 01:32:40.370
- [Rui] We'll have one final question

01:32:40.370 --> 01:32:42.360
from one of the committee members.

01:32:42.360 --> 01:32:43.260
- [Woman] Thank you.

01:32:43.260 --> 01:32:44.410
Thank you very much.

01:32:46.120 --> 01:32:47.500
I'd like to ask a question

01:32:47.500 --> 01:32:49.610
not so much about the economy part.

01:32:49.610 --> 01:32:52.870
But, when you were
speaking about Aristotle

01:32:52.870 --> 01:32:55.780
and being a good citizen and
also the title of your book.

01:32:55.780 --> 01:32:57.300
I started thinking about

01:32:57.300 --> 01:33:00.330
hundreds of years later Michel Foucault.

01:33:00.330 --> 01:33:03.610
And, I'm wondering what you would consider

01:33:03.610 --> 01:33:05.520
the distinction is between I think

01:33:05.520 --> 01:33:10.520
a fundamentally liberal
notion of the good citizen.

01:33:10.630 --> 01:33:15.070
And maybe Foucault's notion
of the governable citizen

01:33:15.070 --> 01:33:16.820
or the governable subject.

01:33:16.820 --> 01:33:19.160
Which has always struck
me as somehow at its core

01:33:19.160 --> 01:33:20.373
not very liberal.

01:33:24.410 --> 01:33:27.700
- This is a time in
which people are reticent

01:33:27.700 --> 01:33:29.573
to criticize liberalism.

01:33:30.600 --> 01:33:34.300
And for good reason 'cause
liberalism is in serious trouble.

01:33:34.300 --> 01:33:37.890
But, one of the reasons why
liberalism is in serious trouble

01:33:37.890 --> 01:33:41.730
is the very limited nature of the idea

01:33:41.730 --> 01:33:43.650
of the individual and the role society.

01:33:43.650 --> 01:33:46.073
Recognizing families and states basically.

01:33:47.230 --> 01:33:50.393
And, that seems to me to be a major flaw.

01:33:53.730 --> 01:33:57.310
So, and if you look at
the history of liberalism

01:33:57.310 --> 01:34:00.380
of course, I mean I
started working on a paper

01:34:00.380 --> 01:34:05.380
which was, if John Stuart
Mill had been Florentine,

01:34:05.960 --> 01:34:08.340
if he'd come from Florence, Italy,

01:34:08.340 --> 01:34:11.770
because there the idea of Librata,

01:34:11.770 --> 01:34:15.600
was a both individual
and a community idea.

01:34:15.600 --> 01:34:19.530
And that was a fundamental
philosophical commitment

01:34:19.530 --> 01:34:20.900
of those places.

01:34:20.900 --> 01:34:22.200
Machiavelli was by the way,

01:34:22.200 --> 01:34:24.120
Machiavelli of The
Discourses was a very good

01:34:24.120 --> 01:34:25.270
representative of that.

01:34:26.280 --> 01:34:28.130
Now, I think that's,

01:34:28.130 --> 01:34:32.440
it's the lack of the emphasis on community

01:34:32.440 --> 01:34:35.363
between family and nation that's the flaw.

01:34:36.200 --> 01:34:39.410
I don't know whether how that relates.

01:34:39.410 --> 01:34:40.690
Why don't you say.

01:34:40.690 --> 01:34:42.280
What do you think the
relationship between that

01:34:42.280 --> 01:34:44.310
of the governablity,

01:34:44.310 --> 01:34:46.410
good governable individual of Foucault is?

01:34:47.590 --> 01:34:49.163
- [Woman] I mean, not his.

01:34:50.650 --> 01:34:51.483
I'm sure there are other people

01:34:51.483 --> 01:34:52.680
who know much more about
Foucault than I do.

01:34:52.680 --> 01:34:56.110
But, I always interpreted
Foucault as saying that

01:34:56.110 --> 01:34:58.280
laws and norms, and schooling

01:34:58.280 --> 01:35:03.280
which you referred to is to
make people sort of docile.

01:35:05.530 --> 01:35:09.080
Live harmoniously according
to the convenience

01:35:09.080 --> 01:35:11.170
of a stably functioning society.

01:35:11.170 --> 01:35:14.190
And that doesn't carry the connotations

01:35:14.190 --> 01:35:17.720
of individual autonomy agency and liberty

01:35:17.720 --> 01:35:20.730
that the liberal vision
of the good citizen

01:35:20.730 --> 01:35:24.810
typically carries, all the
way from Athenian times.

01:35:24.810 --> 01:35:28.710
Which I thought you were more
hearkening to when you spoke.

01:35:28.710 --> 01:35:29.740
That's all.

01:35:29.740 --> 01:35:34.103
- I think that, this
again is a long story.

01:35:35.490 --> 01:35:37.370
If you think of early liberalism

01:35:37.370 --> 01:35:40.050
it was a body of thought
that defended the weak

01:35:40.050 --> 01:35:41.590
against the strong.

01:35:41.590 --> 01:35:43.320
And advocated for tolerance.

01:35:43.320 --> 01:35:46.820
And for example, even the early
advocacy of property rights

01:35:46.820 --> 01:35:49.750
remember, it was advocating
private property rights

01:35:49.750 --> 01:35:52.120
against the States that
were run by the elite

01:35:52.120 --> 01:35:53.263
and run by the rich.

01:35:55.140 --> 01:35:56.730
The idea of private property rights

01:35:56.730 --> 01:35:59.900
was a defense against a State which was

01:35:59.900 --> 01:36:02.490
an autocratic State of the rich.

01:36:02.490 --> 01:36:06.210
And so, if you think about
a lot of early liberalism

01:36:06.210 --> 01:36:11.210
it had a definitely pro
less powerful, outsider.

01:36:12.330 --> 01:36:15.420
Then at a certain point, obviously,

01:36:15.420 --> 01:36:18.940
political liberalism
married economic liberalism.

01:36:18.940 --> 01:36:20.020
Laissez faire.

01:36:20.020 --> 01:36:22.420
And that was the beginning
of the current troubles

01:36:22.420 --> 01:36:24.530
of modern liberalism.

01:36:24.530 --> 01:36:28.500
That turns out to be a
very unstable marriage.

01:36:28.500 --> 01:36:31.550
Because, it went through,
as you surely know

01:36:31.550 --> 01:36:33.150
liberalism was not democratic.

01:36:33.150 --> 01:36:35.610
It became democratic
early in the last century

01:36:35.610 --> 01:36:38.040
when the working class
and women got to vote.

01:36:38.040 --> 01:36:39.860
And now, we have a situation

01:36:39.860 --> 01:36:42.520
of a politically empowered working class

01:36:42.520 --> 01:36:44.950
which is living under an economic model

01:36:44.950 --> 01:36:46.820
which is destroying their communities

01:36:46.820 --> 01:36:49.480
and essentially serving them very ill.

01:36:49.480 --> 01:36:52.680
Well, that's a very dangerous,
dangerous situation.

01:36:52.680 --> 01:36:55.220
And that's, I mean I
recently wrote a paper

01:36:55.220 --> 01:36:57.803
called, The End of Liberalism.

01:36:57.803 --> 01:36:59.460
By the way, it was not a prediction.

01:36:59.460 --> 01:37:02.010
The double entendre was intended.

01:37:02.010 --> 01:37:04.430
The end of liberalism used be defense

01:37:04.430 --> 01:37:06.650
of the weak against the strong.

01:37:06.650 --> 01:37:08.930
So, I meant people to
think maybe it's over

01:37:08.930 --> 01:37:12.240
but maybe we should try
to re-wed liberalism

01:37:12.240 --> 01:37:14.290
to its original ends.

01:37:14.290 --> 01:37:16.620
Having don that I
wouldn't say that is the,

01:37:16.620 --> 01:37:19.130
all that we could expect
from a normative position

01:37:19.130 --> 01:37:20.423
for the good society.

01:37:21.570 --> 01:37:23.870
But, we better defend
it now while we need to.

01:37:24.977 --> 01:37:26.759
- Alright with that,
thank you very very much.

01:37:26.759 --> 01:37:27.717
It's been a pleasure.

01:37:27.717 --> 01:37:30.561
(applause)

01:37:30.561 --> 01:37:32.895
(mumbling)

01:37:32.895 --> 01:37:35.478
(upbeat music)

